n box turnout\n  |  | votes = 21734\n  | percentage = 67.7\n  | change     = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n|  | winner = Labour Party (UK)\n| swing  = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[John Ellis (businessman)|John Ellis]] - [[Quaker]], noted liberal reformer, businessman, Chairman of [[Midland Railway]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Leicester (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester]] and a former owner and resident, along with his family of [[Belgrave Hall]].\n*[[Tony Sibson]] - Professional boxer and former European and Commonwealth middleweight champion, lived in and went to school in Belgrave.\n*[[Jennie Fletcher]] - British competitive [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]], Olympic gold medallist  and former world record-holder, born in Belgrave.\n*[[Tom Sidwell]] - [[cricket]]er, born in Belgrave.\n*[[George Walton (cricketer)|George Walton]] - [[cricket]]er, born and died in Belgrave.\n*[[David Weston (artist)|David Weston]] - [[artist]] and [[author]], born in Belgrave.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/leicester/hi/people_and_places/history/newsid_9290000/9290940.stm Belgrave's first saree shop from [[BBC Radio Leicester]]]\n* {{gbmapping|SK592069}}\n\n{{Wards of Leicester}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Leicester]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belgrave,_Leicester"}
{"title_page": "Belgrave, Tamworth", "text_new": "{{Short description|Area of Tamworth, Staffordshire, roughly {{convert|1 + 1/2|mi}} from the town centre}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n|country =                  England\n|official_name =            Belgrave\n|coordinates              = {{coord|52.61800|-1.67360|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position =           bottom\n|civil_parish =             \n|population =               7,664             \t\n|population_ref =           (2011.Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13694500&c=Belgrave&d=14&e=62&g=6465245&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1449243480117&enc=1|title=Tamworth Ward population 2011 |date=4 December 2015}}</ref> \n|shire_district =           [[Tamworth (borough)|Tamworth]]\n|shire_county =             [[Staffordshire]]\n|region =                   West Midlands      \n|constituency_westminster = [[Tamworth (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]     \n|post_town =                Tamworth\n|postcode_district =        B77        \n|postcode_area =            B77\n|dial_code =                01827\n|os_grid_reference =        \n| london_distance_mi       =     \n| london_direction         = \n| area_total_km2           = \n|static_image =             \n|static_image_caption =     \n}}\n'''Belgrave''' is an area of [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Staffordshire]], roughly {{convert|1 + 1/2|mi}} from the town centre. The main feature of Belgrave is Marlborough way which cuts the area in half. Belgrave contains Tamworth fire station, a [[Morrisons supermarket]], a high school, three primary schools and is bordered by [[Two Gates]], [[Wilnecote]] and [[Glascote]].\n\n==History==\nStarting life as a [[coal mine|mining]] village, on previously agricultural land, Belgrave had its own colliery up until the late 19th century. Other former local industries were [[terracotta]] works and [[car industry|motor manufacturing]]. The area was considerably expanded in the 1970s with the addition of two new housing estates for the 'over-spill' population of [[Birmingham]].<ref>[https://historyofbelgrave.weebly.com/history.html History of Belgrave website]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nBelgrave contains [[Tamworth Enterprise College]] which is a state [[High School]].\n\nBelgrave also contains St Gabriels R C Primary School which is the state [[Roman Catholic]] primary school for [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]].\n\n==Public services==\nTamworth Community Fire station is in Belgrave. Completed in 2010, the station is state-of-the-art including several large meeting rooms, and a gym for use by partners of the station. The station is built on what was previously [[Belgrave High School]] field.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshirefire.gov.uk/ccm/content/press-releases/2008/january-2008/join-the-fire-station-panel-and-have-your-say.en |title=Staffordshire fire and rescue service |access-date=2008-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508015726/http://www.staffordshirefire.gov.uk/ccm/content/press-releases/2008/january-2008/join-the-fire-station-panel-and-have-your-say.en |archive-date=2008-05-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nBelgrave has a pub and a club. These are The Mercian at Exeley centre, and Belgrave Sports and Social Club<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smilelocal.com/sports_and_social_clubs/tamworth |title=Sports and social clubs in the Tamworth area |access-date=2008-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325101615/http://www.smilelocal.com/sports_and_social_clubs/tamworth |archive-date=2009-03-25 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> which hosts regular bingo, private parties, and quality live acts from around the country. (Artists to have played there include Ruby Murray and [[The Drifters]]).\n\n==Transport==\nBelgrave to the north is bordered by the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5 road]] to the north where there is a flyover junction. To the south is [[Watling Street]] which is the old A5 and is now designated as the B5404.\n\nTo the east of Belgrave is the [[Cross Country Route]] and there is a station at nearby [[Wilnecote]].\n\n==Media==\nBelgrave is covered by the [[Tamworth Herald]] newspaper which is the local newspaper for Tamworth.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n[[Belgrave High School]]\n\n{{Areas of Tamworth}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Areas of Tamworth, Staffordshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n|country =                  England\n|official_name =            Belgrave\n|coordinates              = {{coord|52.61800|-1.67360|display=inline,title}}\n|label_position =           bottom\n|civil_parish =             \n|population =               7,664             \t\n|population_ref =           (2011.Ward)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=13694500&c=Belgrave&d=14&e=62&g=6465245&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1449243480117&enc=1|title=Tamworth Ward population 2011 |date=4 December 2015}}</ref> \n|shire_district =           [[Tamworth (borough)|Tamworth]]\n|shire_county =             [[Staffordshire]]\n|region =                   West Midlands      \n|constituency_westminster = [[Tamworth (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]     \n|post_town =                Tamworth\n|postcode_district =        B77        \n|postcode_area =            B77\n|dial_code =                01827\n|os_grid_reference =        \n| london_distance_mi       =     \n| london_direction         = \n| area_total_km2           = \n|static_image =             \n|static_image_caption =     \n}}\n'''Belgrave''' is an area of [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Staffordshire]], roughly {{convert|1 + 1/2|mi}} from the town centre. The main feature of Belgrave is Marlborough way which cuts the area in half. Belgrave contains Tamworth fire station, a [[Morrisons supermarket]], a high school, three primary schools and is bordered by [[Two Gates]], [[Wilnecote]] and [[Glascote]].\n\n==History==\nStarting life as a [[coal mine|mining]] village, on previously agricultural land, Belgrave had its own colliery up until the late 19th century. Other former local industries were [[terracotta]] works and [[car industry|motor manufacturing]]. The area was considerably expanded in the 1970s with the addition of two new housing estates for the 'over-spill' population of [[Birmingham]].<ref>[https://historyofbelgrave.weebly.com/history.html History of Belgrave website]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nBelgrave contains [[Tamworth Enterprise College]] which is a state [[High School]].\n\nBelgrave also contains St Gabriels R C Primary School which is the state [[Roman Catholic]] primary school for [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]].\n\n==Public Services==\nTamworth Community Fire station is located in Belgrave. Completed in 2010, the station is state-of-the-art including several large meeting rooms, and a gym for use by partners of the station. The station is built on what was previously [[Belgrave High School]] field.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.staffordshirefire.gov.uk/ccm/content/press-releases/2008/january-2008/join-the-fire-station-panel-and-have-your-say.en |title=Staffordshire fire and rescue service |access-date=2008-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508015726/http://www.staffordshirefire.gov.uk/ccm/content/press-releases/2008/january-2008/join-the-fire-station-panel-and-have-your-say.en |archive-date=2008-05-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nBelgrave has a pub and a club. These are The Mercian at Exeley centre, and Belgrave Sports and Social Club<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smilelocal.com/sports_and_social_clubs/tamworth |title=Sports and social clubs in the Tamworth area |access-date=2008-12-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325101615/http://www.smilelocal.com/sports_and_social_clubs/tamworth |archive-date=2009-03-25 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> which hosts regular bingo, private parties, and quality live acts from around the country. (Artists to have played there include Ruby Murray and [[The Drifters]]).\n\n==Transport==\nBelgrave to the north is bordered by the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5 road]] to the north where there is a flyover junction. To the south is [[Watling Street]] which is the old A5 and is now designated as the B5404.\n\nTo the east of Belgrave is the [[Cross Country Route]] and there is a station at nearby [[Wilnecote]].\n\n==Media==\nBelgrave is covered by the [[Tamworth Herald]] newspaper which is the local newspaper for Tamworth.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n[[Belgrave High School]]\n\n{{Areas of Tamworth}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Areas of Tamworth, Staffordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belgrave,_Tamworth"}
{"title_page": "Torreya taxifolia", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Torreya taxifolia.jpg\n| image_caption = Leaves of ''Torreya taxifolia''\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn2010>{{Cite iucn |author=Spector, T. |author2=Determann, R. |author3=Gardner, M. |last-author-amp=yes |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |volume=2011 |page=e.T30968A9585489 |date=10 August 2010 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2011-2.RLTS.T30968A9585489.en |accessdate=August 15, 2014 |quote=Listed as Critically Endangered (CR A2ace v3.1)}}</ref>\n| genus = Torreya\n| species = taxifolia\n| authority = [[George Arnott Walker Arnott|Arn.]]\n| range_map = Torreya taxifolia range map.png\n| range_map_caption = Native range\n| synonyms = \n*''Caryotaxus taxifolia'' <small>(Arn.) [[:de:Johann Baptist Henkel|Henkel]] & [[:de:Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter|W.Hochst.]]</small>\n*''Foetataxus taxifolia'' <small>(Arn.) [[K.Koch]]</small>\n*''Tumion taxifolium'' <small>(Arn.) [[Edward Lee Greene|Greene]]</small>\n*''Torreya montana'' <small>[[Hort.]]</small>\n*''Foetataxus montana'' <small>J.Nelson, [[nom. illegit.]]</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=PoWO>{{cite web |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/264000-1 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Henkel1865>{{cite book |last=Henkel |first=Johann Baptist |author-link=:de:Johann Baptist Henkel |last2=Hochstetter |first2=Wilhelm Christian |author-link2=:de:Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter |date=1865 |title=Synopsis der nadelh\u00f6lzer, deren charakteristischen merkmale nebst andeutungen \u00fcber ihre cultur und ausdauer in Deutschlands klima. |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/15220968 |location=Stuttgart |publisher=Verlag der J. G. Cottaschen Buchhandlung |page=367, 368 |language=German |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.15349}}</ref><ref name=INPI4>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/?q=Taxus%20montana |title=''Taxus montana'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Nelson1866>{{cite book |last=Nelson |first=John (under the pseudonym Johannes Senilis) |date=1866 |title=Pinaceae: being a handbook of the firs and pines |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/45263307 |location=London |publisher=Hatchard and co. |page=167, 168 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.84872}}</ref><ref name=FlorPlAtl>{{cite web |url=https://florida.plantatlas.usf.edu/Plant.aspx?id=2330 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' - Species Page |last=Wunderlin |first=Richard P. |last2=Hansen |first2=Bruce F. |last3=Franck |first3=Alan R. |last4=Essig |first4=F. B. |date=17 March 2020 |website=ISB  Atlas of Florida Plants |publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany, University of South Florida, Tampa |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Torreya taxifolia''''', commonly known as the '''Florida nutmeg''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993>{{cite report |author=Esser, Lora L. |date=1993 |title=''Torreya taxifolia''. In: Fire Effects Information System |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/database/feis/plants/tree/tortax/all.html |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Forest Service, Rocky Mountain Research Station, Fire Sciences Laboratory |page= |docket= |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=PLANTS>{{PLANTS |id=TOTA |taxon=Torreya taxifolia |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> '''Florida torreya''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA>{{cite book |last=Hils |first=Matthew H. |date=1993 |chapter=''Torreya taxifolia'' in Taxaceae Gray |chapter-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=220013607 |title=Flora of North America, Vol. 2: Pteridophytes and Gymnosperms |url=http://www.efloras.org/volume_page.aspx?volume_id=1002&flora_id=1 |location=New York and Oxford |publisher=Flora of North America Association |page= |isbn=}} see also: [http://www.efloras.org/object_page.aspx?object_id=5426&flora_id=1 RangeMap]</ref><ref name=Coile1998>{{cite book |last=Coile |first=Nancy C. |date=1998 |title=Notes on Florida's endangered and threatened plants |url=https://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00000172/00001/61x |location=Gainesville |publisher=Florida Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services, Division of Plant Industry |page=55 |isbn=}}</ref><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823033709/http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/ASP/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=4295 |title=National Collection of Imperilled Plants (Center for Plant Conservation) |last=Kadis |first=Irina |date=18 June 2008 |accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Earle2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.conifers.org/ta/Torreya_taxifolia.php |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |last=Earle |first=Christopher J. |date=17 January 2020 |website=The Gymnosperm Database |publisher=Christopher J. Earle |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Alfieri1967>{{cite journal |last=Alfieri |first=S. A., Jr. |last2=Martinez |first2=A. P. |last3=Wehlburg |first3=C. |date=1967 |title=Stem and needle blight of Florida Torreya, ''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/58f7/4e704ed48844a26d41558b8205dad66514f6.pdf |journal=Proceedings of the Florida State Horticultural Society |volume=80 |issue= |pages=428-431 |doi= |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Smith2010>{{cite report |last=Smith |first=Jason Andrew |last2=Trulock |first2=Aaron |date=November 2010 |title=The Decline of Florida Torreya: An Endemic Conifer on the Edge of Extinction |url=https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/fr338 |publisher=School of Forest Resources and Conservation, UF/IFAS Extension, University of Florida |page= |docket=FOR276 |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Alfieri1987>{{cite report |last=Alfieri |first=S. A. |last2=Schoulties |first2=C. L. |last3=Langdon |first3=K. R. |last4=El-Gholl |first4=Nabih Elias |date=January 1987 |title=Leaf and stem disease of ''Torreya taxifolia'' in Florida |url=https://www.fdacs.gov/content/download/11297/file/pp291.pdf |work=Plant Pathology Circular |publisher=Bureau of Plant Pathology, Florida Department Agriculture & Consumer Services |pages=1\u20144 |docket=291 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> '''gopher wood'''<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> or '''stinking-cedar'''<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> is an [[endangered]] tree of the yew [[Family (biology)|family]], [[Taxaceae]],<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> found in the [[Southeastern United States]], at the state border region of northern [[Florida]] and southwestern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=iucn2010/>\n\n''T. taxifolia'' became one of the first federally listed endangered plant species in the United States in 1984;<ref name=FNA/><ref name=USFWS1984>U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. 1984. [http://ecos.fws.gov/docs/federal_register/fr789.pdf ''Federal Register'' (pdf)]</ref> the [[IUCN]] has listed the species as [[critically endangered]] since 1998.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=iucn2000>{{Cite iucn |author=Conifer Specialist Group 2000 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |volume=2000 |page=e.T30968A9585792 |date=2000 |doi= |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> In 2010 98% of the mature trees of the species were believed to be have been destroyed due to a poorly understood fungal blight as well as inundation due to dams and destruction by [[White-tailed deer|deer]] using trees as [[antler]] rubbing posts.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1821 the United States had managed to [[Adams\u2013On\u00eds Treaty|conquer]] the [[Florida Territory]] from [[Spain]] after years of surreptitiously trying to [[Republic of East Florida|usurp Spanish rule]], and begun the process of [[Seminole Wars|ethnically cleansing the land of its previous inhabitants]]. Plantation owners and their stocks of Negro slaves had begun to move south to colonise and exploit the new land. One among them was the patriarch of the wealthy Croom family, who in 1826 purchased land around the town of [[Tallahassee]]. When he died in 1829, his two sons inherited his holdings and resolved to invest further in the region, buying up or leasing numerous plantations and eventually becoming the largest landowners in the area. They had all of their slaves shipped from their North Carolina plantations to labour at clearing the land, cultivating maize and cotton, and building [[Goodwood Plantation|giant mansions]] for their slave-masters. One of the two sons was Hardy Bryan Croom, who besides having studied law, being state senator in North Carolina since his early thirties, and his duties running the family and managing his properties, devoted some time to exploring the sciences.<ref name=McCormick2014>{{cite web |url=http://herbarium.unc.edu/Collectors/Croom_HB.htm |title=Hardy Bryan Croom |last=McCormick |first=Carol Ann |date=4 January 2014 |website=Collectors of the UNC Herbarium |publisher=University of North Carolina Herbarium |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Flowers1979>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/croom-hardy-bryan |title=Croom, Hardy Bryan |last=Flowers |first=John Baxton, III |date=1979 |website=Dictionary of North Carolina Biography |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Croom2005>{{cite web |url=http://www.johncroom.com/croopa19.htm |title=Hardy Bryan Croom |last=Croom |first=John H. |date=19 December 2005 |website=Croom Families and Other Related Surnames |publisher=John H. Croom |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Conrad2012>{{cite magazine |last=Conrad |first=Gibby |date=25 June 2012 |title=The life and death of Hardy Croom, first owner of Goodwood Plantation |url=https://www.tallahasseemagazine.com/the-life-and-death-of-hardy-croom-first-owner-of-goodwood-plantation/ |magazine=Tallahassee Magazine |location=Tallahassee |publisher=Rowland Publishing |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Among other scientific interests,<ref name=Croom2005/> he describes himself as fond of [[botany]], had assembled a small personal [[herbarium]]<ref name=Croom1834/> and posthumously authored a [[monograph]] on the [[carnivorous]] plant genus ''[[Sarracenia]]''.<ref name=Croom2005/>\n\nEast across the [[Apalachicola River|Apalache River]] from the first estate of his brother Bryan Croom in [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden]], who had acquired it in 1826 and coined it 'Rocky Comfort',<ref name=Croom2005/><ref name=Conrad2012/> (another source maintains Hardy Bryan Croom leased the property in 1832), he noted that the flora was quite unique compared to elsewhere in the Tallahassee region,<ref name=Conrad2012/> and sent specimens to the herbaria in the north from 1833,<ref name=McCormick2014/><ref name=Nuttall1849>{{cite book |last=Nuttall |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Nuttall |date=1849 |title=The North American sylva; or, A description of the forest trees of the United States, Canada and Nova Scotia |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433006568038&view=1up&seq=217 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Smith & Wistar |volume=3 |page=91, 92 |doi=}}</ref> and corresponded with the botanist [[John Torrey]] about the plants here from 1834 onwards.<ref name=Croom1834>{{cite book |last=Croom |first=Hardy Bryan |date=1834 |title=Hardy Bryan Croom and John Torrey correspondence, 1834-1837 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53333549 |location=New York |publisher=New York Botanical Garden Archives |page= |doi=}}</ref> Among the [[:wikt:exsiccata|exsiccata]] he sent north in 1833 were samples of a type of yew,<ref name=McCormick2014/> which in his 1834 first letter of reply to an inquiring Torrey he describes as having \"little doubt\" was the ''[[Taxus baccata]]'', the common yew of Europe. His description of the red berries appears to confuse this tree with another rare, local and hitherto undescribed species, [[Taxus floridana|''T. floridana'']].<ref name=Croom1834/>\n\nTorrey realised that Croom was quite mistaken, and that the specimens represented a species new to science.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Croom and his entire family drowned in a shipwreck off the coast of North Carolina in 1837.<ref name=McCormick2014/><ref name=Flowers1979/><ref name=Croom2005/><ref name=Conrad2012/> The novel species was eventually [[Species description|described]] by [[George Arnott Walker Arnott]] in April 1838 from specimens sent to Torrey and collected in Florida by Croom.<ref name=Nuttall1849/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/264000-1 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe species was moved to the [[Synonym (taxonomy)|junior synonym]] ''Caryotaxus taxifolia'' in 1865 by {{ill|Johann Baptist Henkel|de}} and {{ill|Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter|de}} in their monograph on the conifers of the world, ''Synopsis der Nadelh\u00f6lzer''.<!--Note: incorrect authority citation Index Kewensis, PoWO, etc.--><ref name=Henkel1865/> In 1873 [[Karl Koch (botanist)|Karl Heinrich Emil Koch]] moved the species to ''Foetataxus taxifolia''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/262078-1 |title=''Foetataxus taxifolia'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In 1891 [[Edward Lee Greene]] validated [[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque-Schmaltz]]'s [[generic epithet]] ''Tumion'' and erroneously moved this species there as ''Tumion taxifolium''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/258971-2 |title=''Tumion taxifolium'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/11722-1 |title=''Tumion'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn [[Thomas Nuttall]]'s entry about ''Torreya taxifolia'' in his book about American trees, which was published in 1849 although it had been for the most part completed in 1841, he relates that in the correspondence Torrey had sent him, mention had been made of specimens of another species of taxoid tree which had been sent to him by Croom from the same region. To this plant Nuttall \"doubtfully attaches the name\" ''Taxus montana'', somewhat of a [[nomen nudum]], because Nuttall never actually described the plant besides quoting a summary description from Torrey's letter to him. Nuttall is doubtful about the [[taxon]], because according to him it seems \"scarcely distinct\" from [[Taxus brevifolia|''T. brevifolia'']] of the [[Pacific Northwest]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Following the publication of this work, however, he was attributed as the author of this scientific name.<ref name=Henkel1865/><ref name=INPI4/> By 1865 this name was misapplied to ''Torreya taxifolia'' under the name ''Torreya montana''. Henkel and Hochstetter synonymised this taxon with ''T. taxifolia'' in their work mentioned above.<ref name=Henkel1865/> According to the [[Index Kewensis]] this was in error; the name ''Taxus montana'' had actually already been given to a species, now ''[[Prumnopitys montana]]'', described (validated, in fact) in 1806 by [[Carl Ludwig Willdenow]] from specimens collected by [[Alexander von Humboldt]] and [[Aim\u00e9 Bonpland]] on their famous scientific exploration of the Americas, and Nuttall had in fact referred to Willdenow's species.<ref name=INPI4/> [[John Nelson (horticulturist)|John Nelson]], in his more utilitarian as opposed to scientific 1866 horticultural handbook of firs and pines for growing in Britain, introduced the name ''Foetataxus montana'' to write about ''Torreya taxifolia'', apparently unaware of the German publication the previous year.<ref name=Nelson1866/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/262075-1 |title=''Foetataxus montana'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In fact, all these sources were wrong, for Nuttall states that he found a newer specimen of Croom's, of the same taxon, in the Herbarium of the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia]] labelled as ''Taxus floridana''!<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Despite that the original synonymy with ''T. floridana'', all these names are still maintained in the synonymy of ''Torreya taxifolia'' in some modern databases as of 2020.<ref name=PoWO/>\n\nThe [[University of North Carolina]] Herbarium has a single specimen, originally from the Jesup Herbarium of [[Dartmouth College]], sent hither by Croom from the \"Apalache River\" in 1833. Curiously, it was first labelled as \"''Taxus montana'' Willd.\", a South American tree, which was then later changed to ''[[Prumnopitys taxifolia|Podocarpus taxifolia]]'' from southern [[New Zealand]], and finally relabelled as ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=McCormick2014/> \n\n===Higher classification===\nIt is the [[type species]] of the genus ''[[Torreya]]''. The species, and the genus ''Torreya'' in general, has also been placed in the [[Family (biology)|botanical family]] [[Cephalotaxaceae]].<ref name=\"Christenhusz2011\">{{Cite journal |last1=Christenhusz |first1=J. M. M. |last2=Reveal |first2=J. L. |last3=Martin |first3=F. G. |last4=Robert |first4=R. M. |last5=Chase |first5=W. M. |title=Linear sequence, classification, synonymy, and bibliography of vascular plants: Lycophytes, ferns, gymnosperms and angiosperms |year=2011 |journal=Phytotaxa |volume=19 |pages=1\u2013134 |url=http://www.mapress.com/phytotaxa/content/2011/f/pt00019p070.pdf|doi=10.11646/phytotaxa.19.1.1 }}</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\nArnott commemorated Torrey in the generic epithet.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Nuttall1849/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> The [[etymology]] of the [[specific epithet]] is from Latin [[:wikt:taxus#Latin|''taxus'']], meaning 'yew', and [[:wikt:folium#Latin|''folium'']], meaning 'leaf': i.e., 'yew-leaved'.<ref name=Earle2020/><ref>{{cite book |last=Sch\u00fctt |first=Peter |last2=Weisgerber |first2=Horst |last3=Schuck |first3=Hans J. |last4=Lang |first4=K. J. |last5=Stimm |first5=B. |last6=Roloff |first6=A. |date=2004 |title=Lexikon der Nadelb\u00e4ume |url= |location=Hamburg |publisher=Nikol-Verlagsges.mbH |page= |language=German |isbn=3-933203-80-5}}</ref> Other species of ''Torreya'' have longer, less yew-like leaves, but this is not the reason that it was given this name, as the other species were described after this one.<ref name=Earle2020/>\n\n==Common names==\nIt is likely most often known locally by the [[common name]] '''stinking-cedar'''.<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> Another local name used is '''gopher wood'''.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> Nuttall, writing in the early 1840s, coins the name \"yew-leaved torreya\" for it, but describes that in the land where it grows in the 1830s, it was known as \"stinking cedar\", which he ascribes to the \"strong and peculiar odour\" of the timber, especially when it is \"bruised or burnt\". He also mentions the seed, covered in the aril, are approximately the size of a [[nutmeg]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> In 1865 the German botanists Henkel and Hochstetter note that the Americans called the tree \"stinking cedar\" and \"wild nutmeg\". They mention that the name \"nutmeg\" is derived from the bone-hard shelled and acorn-sized seeds, which are covered in an aril somewhat similar to that of true nutmeg. They also describe that when the leaves are crushed they exude a pungent and disagreeable odour, which is why the local Americans used the name \"stinking cedar\". They themselves call the plant \"''Torrey's Nuss-Eibe''\", which translates as \"Torrey's nut-yew\" in English.<ref name=Henkel1865/> According to the gardening writer Nelson in 1866, ''Torreya'' species in general were known as \"stinking cedars\" or \"stinking nutmegs\" by the locals, though he himself recommended the name \"strong-odoured yew\" as preferred for British use. This specific species was called \"stinking cedar\" by the Americans according to him, although he recommended the name \"mountain yew\" for Britain -this is a calque of the (incorrect) Latin name he was using, he was apparently unaware of the fact that this species grows almost at sea level and nowhere near any mountains!<ref name=Nelson1866/> In fact, of all species of ''Torreya'', it is only the species which is never found in mountainous areas.\n\n[[Image:T taxifolia.jpg|thumb|Seed cone]]\n\nAlthough the [[vernacular name]] '''Florida torreya''' was formally recommended by most conservation works and internet databases,<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> this was changed to '''Florida nutmeg''' in the late 2010s.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=PLANTS/> Other names for this tree are '''savin''',<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''polecat wood''',<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''yew-leaved torreya''',<ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=Nuttall1849/> '''foetid yew''',<ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''stinking cedar''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=USBG>{{cite web |url=https://m.usbg.gov/plants/stinking-cedar |title=Stinking cedar |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher=United States Botanic Garden |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> '''mountain yew''' (Britain)<ref name=Nelson1866/> or '''stinking yew'''{{cn|date=March 2020}} (applied to the Californian species ''[[Torreya californica]]'').<ref name=Nelson1866/>\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:The North American sylva (Pl. CIX) (9150099237).jpg|thumb|Plate from Nuttall's ''The North American sylva'', published 1849. It is captioned: \"A branch of the male plant, natural size. ''a''. Male [[Catkin|amentum]]. ''b''. Back view of one of the [[stamen]]s magnified. ''c''. Female ament and [[ovule]], magnified. ''d''. Section of the ripe seed. ''e''. Germinating seed.\"<ref name=Nuttall1849/>]]\n\n''Torreya taxifolia'' is an [[evergreen]] [[tree]] that may reach heights of {{convert|18|m}} with an {{convert|80|cm}} diameter trunk,<ref name=FNA/> although it typically grew to {{convert|9|-|12|m|ft}} tall and {{convert|30|-|50|cm|in}} in diameter,<ref name=Esser1993/> and most stands today are composed of immature trees of less than {{convert|3|m}} tall.<ref name=iucn2000/> The crown is open and conical in overall shape,<ref name=FNA/> with whorled branches.<ref name=Coile1998/> These branches are spreading to slightly drooping. The bark of two-year old branches are coloured yellowish-green, yellowish-brown or grey.<ref name=FNA/> The young branchlets divide into threes.<ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\nThe stiff, needle-like [[leaf|leaves]] are sharp to the touch,<ref name=Coile1998/> {{convert|1.5|-|3.8|cm|in}} long<ref name=FNA/> and 3&nbsp;mm broad.{{cn|date=March 2020}} These are arranged in two ranks on the branches<ref name=Alfieri1967/> and are coloured glossy green above and light green below,<ref name=Coile1998/> with a very slightly sunken grayish stripe of [[stomata]] on either side of the midrib on the underside,<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/> and slightly round in transverse profile on the topside.<ref name=FNA/> The leaves have an unpleasant, strongly pungent, resinous odor when crushed.<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/>\n\nIt is [[dioecious]], with separate male and female plants.<ref name=iucn2010/> The male ([[pollen]]) [[conifer cone|cones]] resemble those of a common yew, but are much larger and have [[imbricate]]d scales ([[bract]]s) at their base.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> They are 5\u20137&nbsp;mm long, grouped in lines along the underside of a shoot. The female ([[seed]]) cones are single or grouped two to five together on a short stem; minute at first, they mature in about 18 months to a [[drupe]]-like structure with the single large [[nut (fruit)|nut]]-like seed{{cn|date=March 2020}} surrounded by a fleshy covering called an [[aril]], {{convert|2.5|-|3.5|cm|in}} long including aril,<ref name=FNA/> about the size of a nutmeg.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> The aril is [[:wikt:glaucous|glaucous]] and coloured dark green and streaked with purple at full maturity in the fall.<ref name=FNA/> Unlike true yews, in which the aril forms a \"cup\" around the seed, in this plant the aril completely encloses the seed, leaving only a minute perforation at the end. The aril is fleshy in consistency, like a fruit.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> When the aril is removed, the seed bears a striking resemblance to a large acorn.<ref name=Henkel1865/><ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[Image:Torreya taxifolia foliage.jpg|thumb|Foilage]]\n\n''Torreya taxifolia'' is restricted to [[limestone]] bluffs and [[ravine]]s along the east bank of the [[Apalachicola River]] in the central part of the northern [[Florida Panhandle]] and immediately adjacent southernmost [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=iucn2010/> near the town of [[Chattahoochee, Florida]];<ref name=Alfieri1987/> there is also a small colony west of the Apalachicola at Dog Pond in [[Jackson County, Florida|Jackson County]].<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Schwartz1993>{{cite journal |last=Schwartz |first=Mark William |last2=Hermann |first2=Sharon M. |date=July 1993 |title=The Continuing Population Decline of ''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |url= |journal=Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club |volume=120 |issue=3 |pages=275-286 |doi=10.2307/2996992}}</ref> It grows along the Apalachicola River just south of the confluence of the [[Chattahoochee River]] and the [[Flint River (Georgia)|Flint River]], which reach northwards through [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]] and [[Atlanta]] to drain the southern [[Blue Ridge Mountains]], a subrange of the [[Appalachian Mountains]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> It only occurs in the Florida counties of [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden]], Jackson and [[Liberty County, Florida|Liberty]], and extends one mile into [[Decatur County, Georgia]]<ref name=Esser1993/> (another source states the northernmost wild individual currently growing in Georgia is within {{convert|200|m|ft}} of the Florida state line). The outlying population west of the Apalachicola, in Jackson County, has always been small: In 1938 H. Kurz reported it to be restricted to one stand with a few trees,<ref name=Schwartz2000>{{cite journal |last=Schwartz |first=Mark William |last2=Hermann |first2=Sharon M. |last3=Van Mantgem |first3=Philip J. |date=August 2000 |title=Estimating the magnitude of decline of the Florida torreya (''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn.) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261805791 |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=77-84 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(00)00008-2 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> in 1974 this was reported as consisting of 60 trees,<ref name=Esser1993/> and in 1989 Mark William Schwartz and R. Nicholson reported it to consist of five trees.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThe area in which it naturally occurs is {{convert|203|km2|acres}}, stretching {{convert|35|km|miles}} along the Apalachicola River.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThere is a small introduced population on the Biltmore Estate in [[Asheville, North Carolina]], where it was planted as an [[ornamental plant]].<ref name=Esser1993/>\n\n===Prehistoric distribution===\nA number of sources state that this species has been recorded from fossils which suggest that at one time it grew over much of the eastern United States and that it has existed for 165 million years;<ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=USBG/> this is incorrect.<ref name=Barlow2015>{{cite report |last=Barlow |first=Connie |date=August 2015 |title=Paleoecology and the Assisted Migration Debate: Why a Deep-Time Perspective is Vital (''Torreya taxifolia'' as exemplar) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/288671815 |publisher=Torreya Guardians |page=1\u201411 |doi=10.13140/RG.2.1.4299.0166 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Only two fossil examples are known of ''Torreya'' in eastern North America. The first was a species with dense, spirally arranged leaves described as [[Torreya caroliniana|''Tunion carolinianum'']] by [[Edward W. Berry]] in 1908 from the Mid-[[Cretaceous]] of North Carolina,<ref name=Berry1908>{{cite journal |last=Berry |first=Edward Wilber |date=1 May 1908 |title=A Mid-Cretaceous species of ''Torreya''; ''Tunion carolinianum'' sp. nov. |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1662627 |journal=American Journal of Science |volume=25 |issue=149 |pages=382\u2014386 |doi=10.2475/ajs.s4-25.149.382 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> the second is only known from a single piece of fossilised wood from the [[Upper Cretaceous]], also from North Carolina, which has been described as ''[[Torreya antiqua]]''.<ref name=Boeshore1936>{{cite journal |last=Boeshore |first=Irwin |last2=Gray |first2=William D. |date=1 October 1936 |title=An Upper Cretaceous Wood: ''Torreya antiqua'' |url= |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=23 |issue=8 |pages=524-528 |doi=10.1002/j.1537-2197.1936.tb09019.x}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nIt grows at altitudes of {{convert|15|-|30|m|ft}}, mostly on wooded ravines, bluffs and steep,<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> north-facing slopes.<ref name=iucn2010/> These ravines have nearly permanent seeps. It also occurs in the bottoms of ravines and adjacent floodplains.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> It grows in the shade under the canopy of larger trees.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The soils of this region are [[:wikt:calcareous|calcareous]],<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Nuttall1849/> moist, dark-coloured, sandy loams.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/>\n\nIt occurs in two types of habitats restricted to the river drainage, an oak-[[tupelo]]-cypress forest or an oak-pine forest.<ref name=Esser1993/> These forests are mostly [[deciduous]], but evergreen hardwoods and conifers are also common.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> R. M. Harper, who travelled throughout northern Florida by horse and train to document the compositions of various forests, stated in 1914 that the most frequent species in the Apalachicola ravines were ''[[Magnolia grandiflora]]'' (9.5%), spruce pine (''[[Pinus glabra]]'', 5.6%, American beech (''[[Fagus grandifolia]]'', 4.1%) and the understory ''Torreya taxifolia'' (4.0%) and ''Ilex opaca'' (3.5%).<ref name=Schwartz2000/> According to the IUCN the large trees in this habitat are ''[[Fagus grandifolia]]'', tulip tree (''[[Liriodendron tulipifera]]''), [[Acer floridanum|''Acer barbatum'']], sweetgum (''[[Liquidambar styraciflua]]''), white oak (''[[Quercus alba]]''), and occasionally loblolly pine (''[[Pinus taeda]]'') and ''[[Pinus glabra]]''.<ref name=iucn2010/> [[Magnolia]]s also grow in these woods.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Often these woods are hung with vines such as ''[[Smilax]]'' species and crossvine (''[[Bignonia capreolata]]'').<ref name=iucn2010/> Another rare conifer, the Florida yew (''[[Taxus floridana]]''), occasionally grows with ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Vaughan2001>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040725080037/http://www.hort.agri.umn.edu:80/h5015/rrr.htm |title=Restoration of longleaf pine and wiregrass at the Apalachicola Bluffs Preserve (Florida) |last=Vaughan |first=Elizabeth |date=2001 |website=Volume 7- Fall 2001: Lessons Learned From Long-Term Restorations. Restoration and Reclamation Review, Student On-Line Journal (Hort 5015/5071) |publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> A rare salamander found in these ravines is ''[[Desmognathus apalachicolae]]''. The ravines boast the southernmost parts of the ranges of a number of more northern species such as the plants ''[[Hydrangea quercifolia]]'', ''[[Epigaea repens]]'' and ''[[Kalmia latifolia]]'' and the copperhead snake ''[[Agkistrodon contortrix]]''.<ref name=Vaughan2001/> Upland around these woodlands are [[flatwoods]], which are a longleaf pine/wiregrass (''[[Pinus palustris]]''/''[[Aristida stricta]]'') sandhill plant community.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Vaughan2001/> It is uncommon in its native habitats, with individuals spaced far apart.<ref name=Esser1993/>\n\nVarious animals eat the seeds.<ref name=Esser1993/> Rodents favour the seeds.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Squirrels apparently remove the seeds, which they eat, from the arils, which they do not eat, and often store them in [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|caches]] for the winter, where they may sprout into new trees.<ref name=Barlow2001>{{Cite magazine |last=Barlow |first=Connie |date=2001 |title=Anachronistic Fruits and the Ghosts Who Haunt Them |url=http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/618.pdf |magazine=Arnoldia |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=19-21 |location=Boston, Massachusetts |publisher=Arnold Arboretum of Harvard University |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Torreya Park Apalachicola River pano02.jpg|thumb|250px|View of [[Apalachicola River]] at [[Torreya State Park]]]]\n\nIn a 2001 newsletter, the writer Connie Barlow suggested that ''T. taxifolia'' may be an [[evolutionary anachronism]] similar to the Osage orange (''[[Maclura pomifera]]'') and Kentucky coffeetree (''[[Gymnocladus dioicus]]''), which are thought to have been dispersed by a now-extinct animal. She made this suggestion based on the fact that this species is rare, that it grew well in the cooler temperatures of [[North Carolina]], and her belief that the species was only found on the east bank of the Apalachicola and was unable to disperse to the west bank with the animals she thought might be the main dispersal agents today, squirrels. She theorised than during the [[Eemian|last interglacial]] (the geologically short periods between [[ice age]]s) and the proceeding ones, the species grew further north. According to her theories, because there might have been an unknown and now extinct animal in the past which was better suited to eat and defecate the seeds, or otherwise move the seeds, the species was now \"stuck\" behind the Apalachicola which served as a refuge habitat for a [[Relict (biology)|relict population]] during the long periods of glacial conditions which characterised the [[Pleistocene]]. She further supposed that because the arils contain [[terpene]]s which are usually toxic for mammals, and the seed's shell is so thin that mammal molars would crush the seeds, that the purported extinct animal might not be a mammal and instead suggested some unknown species of large [[tortoise]] as the extinct ecological partner.<ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n==Uses==\nIt is has been far too rare to harvest commercially since the 1950s, but it has a beautiful, yellow-coloured, close-grained wood. The timber is lightweight, hard, strong and highly durable.<ref name=Esser1993/> In the 19th century, the tree was harvested for wood that was used as fence posts,<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> shingles,<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> cabinets,<ref name=Esser1993/> [[Christmas tree]]s,<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Esser1993/> firewood,<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> and as a fuel for riverboats on the [[Apalachicola River]].<ref name=iucn2010/> Fences made of this wood in the 1910s were still good in the 1970s.<ref name=Esser1993/> In the 1830s it was locally abundant enough for the trees to be harvested to be sawn into planks, which were much used in the construction of the village of [[Aspalaga Landing]]. In this era it was also recommended as making excellent posts for fencing, not being liable to attack by insects.<ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\nWhen the trunks are damaged, the trees yield a small quantity of pasty, viscous, blood-red [[turpentine]], which can be dissolved in alcohol, but has a very powerful and unpleasant odour.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> \n\n===Cultivation===\nThe tree is well-represented in cultivation, and is widely planted outside of its native range as an ornamental, and is found in private gardens, [[arboretum|arboreta]] and botanical gardens.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/>\n\nIt was first imported to grow in Europe in 1840. Large trees were to be found in [[Germany]] by the 1860s.<ref name=Henkel1865/> It is tolerably hardy, but grows very slowly in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], and as such was only recommended for collectors.<ref name=Nelson1866/>\n\nIt has occasionally been planted as a landscape tree around [[Tallahassee]], and one such specimen in [[Lee, Florida]] has achieved {{convert|30|ft}}.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Some large specimens are grown elsewhere in botanical gardens. The [[champion tree]] of the species is in a private garden in [[Norlina, North Carolina]], having a height of {{convert|45|ft}}, a trunk diameter of {{convert|88|cm}} [[Diameter at breast height|dbh]] and a canopy width of {{convert|40|ft}} in 1996.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> It has been said to endure winter temperatures of {{convert|-31|C}} in North Carolina without much problem.<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n===Propagation===\nCuttings of ''Torreya'' shoot-tips often show fungal contamination. Experimental studies with weekly sprayed applications of a combinations of [[Systemic pesticide|systemic]] [[fungicide]]s, such as [[thiophanate-methyl]] combined with [[zinc]] and [[Maneb]] or [[thiabendazole]], were able to eliminate the fungi from stock plants after four weeks, although these preparations were not US government approved as of 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> \n\nTissue culture methods of propagation were being investigated as of 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe first person to notice that the trees were dying was the forester L. T. Nieland in 1938, although he never wrote a formal paper about it. In the same year Kurz made a detailed study of the ecology of species and mentioned that there was no danger to the species vanishing from its habitat if lumbering would cease.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> In 1954 Kurz and R. K. Godfrey surveyed the population and noticed no symptoms of decline. However, in 1962 Godfrey and Kurz, having surveyed the species again, reported that the natural stands of this species, which was historically never widely distributed, were dying off and extinction seemed assured, if not already accomplished.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962>{{cite journal |last=Godfrey |first=R. K. |last2=Kurz |first2=H. |date=1962 |title=The Florida Torreya destined for extinction |url= |journal=Science |volume=136 |pages=900-902 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> By 1962, only non-reproductive sprouts regrowing from the top-killed stumps remained in the wild,<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962/> a situation which has persisted throughout the 20th century.<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> They attributed this to deforestation due to the lumber trade.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962/> However, samples of the afflicted trees were sent to the [[University of Florida]], where Erdman West suggested the decline appeared due to a fungal blight of some kind. In a 1967 article S. A. Alfieri Jr. ''et al''. of the [[Florida Department of Agriculture]] presented their research of the phenomenon. The disease presents itself as a small, yellowish spot on the needles (leaves) -one or more per leaf, which soon spreads throughout the leaf until it dies, turns brown and falls off. Subsequently the disease spreads into the twig, and all of the needles fall off, leaving only a tuft of new growth at the tip. The disease spreads in stages, first affecting portions, later the entire tree. Severely infected trees eventually loose most of their needles and twigs. Fungal fruiting structures grow on wholly necrotic tissue on the underside of the leaves, twigs and buds. In some cases, the stems of affected or dead trees also showed fungal [[canker]]. Young seedlings are also affected, but less severely than older trees. Trees growing in the shade are more affected than those in full sunlight.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> \n\nIn 1985 the [[phytopathologist]] Nabih Elias El-Gholl, also of the Florida Department of Agriculture, was able to prove that there were at least two pathogens involved; the leaf-spot disease presented as light greyish-green spots, which later became tan-coloured, and were up to 8.4mm long and as wide as the needle, with brown, irregularly-shaped, 2.4mm long \u00d7 2mm wide, necrotic centres and were able to infect the plants in the absence of wounds within three days of inoculation. Initially only a few spots, maximally four, developed per plant. After some two weeks the infected needles died and fell off -by this time the undersides had developed spore structures,<ref name=El-Gholl1985>{{cite journal |last=El-Gholl |first=Nabih Elias |date=1985 |title=''Fusarium lateritium'' Causing Needle Spots on ''Torreya taxifolia'' in Florida |url=https://www.apsnet.org/publications/PlantDisease/BackIssues/Documents/1985Abstracts/PD_69_905a.htm |journal=Plant Disease |volume=69 |pages=905 |doi=10.1094/PD-69-905a |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> which were primarily found along the two grey bands of stomata, but may also occur on the twigs.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nThe canker disease presents as elongated [[fusiform]] swellings on the stems which eventually may break open. They are often found at the base of the trees.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nIn 1993 Schwartz, who has spent much of his career researching the conservation of this species, and Sharon M. Hermann, reported on the progression of the disease. They monitored a census population of some 100 trees for four years, in this time 10% died, mostly the smaller individuals. Most plants consisted of multi-stemmed, regenerating stumps; the mean length of the longest stems were less than one meter. Less than half of the plants showed any growth in length during these four years, and 32% lost their primary stem, which meant the mean size of individuals within the population was decreasing. Death was not strongly related to specific location or if the plants showed disease symptoms, although stem mortality was higher with trees showing a higher severity of foliar pathogens.<ref name=Schwartz1993/> In 2000 Schwartz ''et al''. reported that despite Godfrey and Kurz's 1962 prediction, a small population size, continued population losses, and no known seed production for decades, extinction of ''T. taxifolia'' had not yet occurred, and although the population would likely steadily decline, it was unlikely to go extinct within the next 50 years.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\n===Status===\nThis was one of the first federally listed {{C|Endangered flora of the United States|endangered plant species in the United States}} in 1984 (Federal Register 1/23/84).<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=USFWS1984/> It is one of only two species of conifer protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=Earle2020/> It was listed as \"[[threatened species|threatened]]\" within the state of Florida by 1987 (Florida Statutes Section 581.185),<ref name=Alfieri1987/> again in 1994 by the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission,<ref name=Esser1993/> and in 1998 the status in Florida was changed to \"[[endangered]]\".<ref name=PLANTS/><ref name=Coile1998/> In 2002 it was added to the list of \"endangered\" plants of Georgia.<ref name=PLANTS/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> It has been a \"[[critically endangered]]\" species on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 1998, in 2000 this was said to be due to estimated 98% decline in mature individuals since the early 1950s.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=iucn2000/>\n\n===Population===\nIn 2000 Schwartz and colleagues calculated that before the start of the decline, the original population of ''T. taxifolia'' may have been 300,000 between 650,000 plants, with 357,500 individual trees being the preferred estimate, based on a historic abundance of 14.2% of dominant ravine trees in 1914, or 30 trees/ha, and a historic distribution of some {{convert|203|km2|acres}}.<ref name=Schwartz2000/> Only 27 trees were counted in Georgia in 1981.<ref name=iucn2000/> In 1993 Schwartz estimated that there were only 1500 trees in the wild.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Schwartz1993/> Based on the extrapolation of a survey of five stands of the 2000 survey, attenuated with assumptions that these stands were the most dense, Schwartz ''et al''. calculated the population in its native habitat to be between 500 and 4,000 individuals, with none capable of reproduction. The most likely population was calculated to be 1,361 individuals, not including the population west of the Apalachicola. Using their estimate of the pre-decline population, they thus calculated a minimum 98.5% decline in population over the last 50 years.<ref name=Schwartz2000/> The [[IUCN]] estimated that the population is 999 mature individuals in its native habitat (although, confusingly, it also states the population to consist of between 500 and 600 trees elsewhere in the assessment), of which less than ten were known to produce male or female cones.<ref name=iucn2010/> It stated that the population continued to decrease,<ref name=iucn2010/> although the decline may be reversible should the causes of infection be better understood.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Schwartz2000/> IUCN population viability analyses indicate that [[extinction]] within its native range is inevitable.<ref name=iucn2010/>\n\nThe IUCN stated the total [[extent of occurrence]] is estimated to be about {{convert|200|km2|acres}},<ref name=iucn2010/> this is the same as the historical distribution. Schwartz states that these has been no logging in its habitat since the 1950s and that this species has experienced no [[habitat loss]]: the vast majority of the original ravine forest habitat remains.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\n===Threats===\nThe most significant current threat to the species is the continued reproductive failure associated with [[fungal]] pathogens.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Smith2010/> Individuals do not reach reproductive size before being top-killed.<ref name=iucn2010/> Almost no plants are able to reach a reproductive size, and where seeds do form, these are soft, crumbly and not viable.<ref name=Esser1993/> Up to ten species of fungi have been found growing in infected ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date= |title=''Fusarium torreyae'' sp nov., a pathogen causing canker disease of Florida torreya (''Torreya taxifolia''), a critically endangered conifer restricted to northern Florida and southwestern Georgia |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232705140 |journal= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlfieri ''et al''. were able to [[Isolate (biology)|isolate]] five species of fungi in 1967 from the stems and leaves, but failed to isolate any of the fungi from the cankered stems on the media they were using, [[potato dextrose agar]]. They reported that the disease appeared to implicate species tentatively identified as ''[[Physalospora]]'' and ''[[Macrophoma]]'', but also isolated the fungi ''[[Rhizoctonia solani]]'', ''[[Sclerotium rolfsii]]'' and a ''[[Sphaeropsis]]'' species from the infected tissue.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> They attempted to reproduce the infections by spraying the isolates, as well as pulverised [[Plant litter|stem and leaf litter]], on seedlings grown in greenhouses from unaffected ornamental trees in local parks, but their experiments failed to induce the disease in their seedlings.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> Nonetheless reports from 1975 and 1988 continued to identify the responsible fungi as these previous two species.<ref name=Esser1993/> In 1985 El-Gholl was finally able to prove [[Koch's postulates]] with ''[[Gibberella baccata]]'' (as ''[[Fusarium lateritium]]'', an [[Teleomorph, anamorph and holomorph|anamorph]] isolate) as the agent responsible for the leaf spot pathogen, but he was unable to replicate the disease causing the stem cankers.<ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=El-Gholl1985/><ref name=MycoBank>{{cite web |url=http://www.mycobank.org/Biolomics.aspx?Table=Mycobank&Rec=34922&Fields=All |title=''Gibberella baccata'' |last=Bensch |first=K. |date=2020 |website=MycoBank |publisher=International Mycological Association (IMA) and the Westerdijk Fungal Biodiversity Institute |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 1987 Alfieri ''et al''. reported on experiments with this fungus, as well as another two more species isolated from the infected plants, ''[[Xylocoremium flabelliforme]]'' (the anamorph state of ''[[Xylaria cubensis]]'') and the ''Macrophoma'' which they had re-identified as a ''[[Phyllosticta]]'' species, the anamorph form of ''[[Guignardia]]''. They were able to reproduce El-Gholl's results, but again failed to identify the canker producing agent, the other two isolates proved not to cause any disease.<ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> In a 1996 article Lee ''et al''. mentioned that the [[endophyte]] they were studying, ''[[Pestalotiopsis microspora]]'' might be the cause of the decline of the species, because a strain they isolated produced a hitherto unknown [[cytotoxin]] they named \"[[torreyanic acid]]\", a [[Merosity|dimeric]] [[quinone]].<ref name=Lee1996>{{cite journal |last=Lee |first=Julie Chu-Li |last2=Strobel |first2=Gary A. |last3=Lobkovsky |first3=Emil |last4=Clardy |first4=Jon |date=17 May 1996 |title=Torreyanic Acid: A Selectively Cytotoxic Quinone Dimer from the Endophytic Fungus ''Pestalotiopsis microspora'' |journal=The Journal of Organic Chemistry |volume=61 |issue=10 |pages=3232\u20133233 |doi=10.1021/jo960471x}}</ref> ''P. microspora'' is a usually [[Commensalism|commensal]] fungus commonly found within the tissues of many plant species, and is only rarely a pathogen -in these cases it is an [[Opportunistic infection|opportunistic pathogen]].<ref name=Smith2010/> However, recent research has identified a previously unknown species of ''[[Fusarium]]'' may be the cause.<ref name=iucn2010/> \n\nBy 1987 the canker disease had spread to plants cultivated outside the native range such as in the [[University of Florida]] campus in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and in the [[Alfred B. Maclay Gardens State Park]] in Tallahassee.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> \n\nAccording to one older theory logging of shade trees may stress individuals of this species, which does not like being suddenly exposed to full sunlight, conducing infection.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/>\n\nAnother threat to the population is destruction by [[White-tailed deer|deer]].<ref name=iucn2010/> Deer preferentially select young trees of this species to rub their new antlers on, sometimes killing them. Feral pigs may also uproot and destroy seedlings.<ref name=Esser1993/> Another possible cause of the historical decline may be changes in the environment due to fire suppression, and changes in water tables linked to the construction of dams.<ref name=iucn2010/> Specifically, many trees were killed when the land was flooded<ref name=Esser1993/> in the construction of the [[Jim Woodruff Dam]] impounding [[Lake Seminole]].<ref name=USBG/>\n\nAccording to one writer, the population of the species may have been impacted by postglacial [[global warming]], as it may possibly be better adapted to the cooler climate found in Florida during the last [[ice age]]. It may not have been able to move north due to poor dispersal abilities. This is based on the fact that the introduced population on the Biltmore estate in North Carolina appears to be doing fine, and is even reproducing naturally -squirrels plant the seeds in the flower beds and these germinate.<ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n===Actions===\n[[Fungicide]] treatment with [[Maneb]] has been shown to be remarkably effective, with plants showing renewed growth afterwards with little to no fungal infection. It has been applied since 1967,<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1967/> but as of 1987 it is not specifically labelled for use in ''Torreya''.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nA theory perhaps first put forward in 1990 by Greg Seamon, land manager at the [[Apalachicola Bluffs and Ravines Preserve]], was that ''Torreya taxifolia'' may be somehow suffering from the suppression of fire in the upland longleaf pine-wiregrass sandhill ecosystems. However, after regular fires were again instituted in the 1990s in the preserve, this appeared not to have an effect, with the species experiencing an increased three percent annual mortality at the turn of the century.<ref name=Vaughan2001/>\n\nTwo years after declaring the species an endangered species, in 1986, the [[U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] published a recovery plan. The chief tactic was to produce a genetically diverse collection of trees for reproduction and reintroduction into the wild. Other priorities were to protect the habitat of remaining populations, and to study the disease and methods of [[Plant propagation|propagation]].<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/>\n\nPlants in general attract very little funding compared to [[vertebrate]]s, this tree is no different. The US federal government spent only $1,500 on conservation of the species in 1993, placing it 884th out of 926 endangered species. Schwartz ''et al''. stated that recovery is possible, but this will require a greater level of commitment and a dedicated increase in funding.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nSmall experiments by Schwartz and Hermann in the 1990s found that planting cuttings in the native habitat is possible. Schwartz ''et al''. recommended population augmentation by planting volunteers isolated by more than 100m from extant stands to reduce chance of contamination.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThe tree is well-represented in cultivation, and is widely planted for conservation purposes outside of its native range.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> Plants outside of its historic native distribution are undamaged by fungal disease and produce viable seed.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Schwartz2000/> In Tallahassee for example, not far from the native range, a number of large trees had been grown for almost a century in the Alfred B. Maclay Gardens without problems and had been successfully propagated here since the 1960s,<ref name=Alfieri1967/> although the trees in this park became infected by the canker disease by 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> It is found in [[arboretum|arboreta]], botanical gardens and elsewhere throughout the world.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> In the [[Netherlands]], for example, it is grown in the [[Arboretum Trompenburg]], the {{ill|Arboretum Oudenbosch|nl}}, the [[Hortus Haren]], the [[Hortus Botanicus Amsterdam]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.botanischetuinen.nl/planten/plant/1641/torreya-taxifolia/ |title=Florida torreya |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Plantzoeker |publisher=Nederlandse Vereniging van Botanische Tuinen |language=Dutch |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> and the {{ill|Pinetum Blijdenstein|nl}}.<ref>{{cite report |authors=Stichting Pinetum Blijdenstein |date=July 2016 |title=Pinetum Blijdenstein \u2014 Beleidsplan 2016 \u2013 2020 v.1.0 |url=https://api1.ibabs.eu/publicdownload.aspx?site=hilversum&id=100131346 |publisher=Stichting Pinetum Blijdenstein |page=22 |language=Dutch |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States the [[Center for Plant Conservation]] maintains the species in its National Collection of Endangered Plants; the [[Arnold Arboretum]] of [[Harvard University]] is the primary custodian of this species.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The [[Atlanta Botanical Garden]] and the [[State Botanical Garden of Georgia]] are actively propagating the plant for conservation purposes. These are members of the Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance, which is protecting the species by growing seedlings and cuttings, and planting these both ''[[in situ]]'' and ''[[ex situ]]''.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=USBG/><ref name=UGAbotGar>{{cite report |author= |date=April 2008 |title=GPCA Safeguarding Policy Statement - Policy Statement Regarding ''in situ'' and ''ex situ'' Plant Conservation Between Members of the Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance |url=https://botgarden.uga.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/GPCA-Safeguarding-Policy-Statement-.pdf |publisher=Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance |pages=1-10 |docket= |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Plants are also grown at the [[United States Botanic Garden]].<ref name=USBG/> \n\nIn her intriguing but somewhat unsubstantiated 2001 newsletter article Barlow synthesized her suppositions to suggest that the only way to conserve the species was for humans to engage in [[assisted migration]], transplanting across great distances. She noted that, in essence, humans are now the gardeners artificially preserving most isolated islands of \"wilderness\" amongst a sea of human development, if we like it or not.<ref name=Barlow2001/> In this she was not unique, in 1994 Foote and Jones had already written that the survival of this species was likely dependent upon cultivation in gardens.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The idea is that ''T. taxifolia'' for some reason was unable to migrate north from its \"ice age pocket refuge\" in northern Florida.<ref name=Fox2007>{{cite magazine |last=Fox |first=Douglas |date=January 2007 |title=When worlds collide |url=http://conservationmagazine.org/2008/07/when-worlds-collide/ |magazine=Conservation |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=28-34 |location= |publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> This inspired the formation of a group, Torreya Guardians, which are attempting to [[rewilding (conservation biology)|rewild]] ''Torreya taxifolia'' trees in cooler mountain areas in the southern [[Appalachians]] in an attempt to aid the species.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torreyaguardians.org/rewilding.html |title=Rewilding ''Torreya taxifolia''? |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=April 2015 |publisher=Torreya Guardians |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Some conservationists consider ''T. taxifolia'' as the lead candidate for assisted migration.<ref name=Fox2007/> This project has proved contentious.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Nijhuis |first=Michelle |date=May\u2013June 2008 |title=Taking Wildness in Hand: Rescuing Species |url=http://www.orionmagazine.org/index.php/articles/article/2966/ |magazine=Orion Magazine |pages=64\u201378 |location=Great Barrington, Massachusetts |publisher=The Orion Society |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Protected areas===\nThe natural populations are largely [[protected area|protected]] within the [[Torreya State Park]]<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/> and at the [[Nature Conservancy]]'s [[Apalachicola Bluffs and Ravines Preserve]] (first parcels purchased in 1982 to protect the ravines, before the species was officially listed as endangered).<ref name=Vaughan2001/>\n\n==References and external links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Reflist|refs=}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q595832}}\n\n[[Category:Torreya|taxifolia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Florida]]\n[[Category:Flora of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Southeastern United States]]\n[[Category:Apalachicola River|~]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered flora of the United States]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1838]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of plant}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Torreya taxifolia.jpg\n| image_caption = Leaves of ''Torreya taxifolia''\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn2010>{{Cite iucn |author=Spector, T. |author2=Determann, R. |author3=Gardner, M. |last-author-amp=yes |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |volume=2011 |page=e.T30968A9585489 |date=10 August 2010 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2011-2.RLTS.T30968A9585489.en |accessdate=August 15, 2014 |quote=Listed as Critically Endangered (CR A2ace v3.1)}}</ref>\n| genus = Torreya\n| species = taxifolia\n| authority = [[George Arnott Walker Arnott|Arn.]]\n| range_map = Torreya taxifolia range map.png\n| range_map_caption = Native range\n| synonyms = \n*''Caryotaxus taxifolia'' <small>(Arn.) [[:de:Johann Baptist Henkel|Henkel]] & [[:de:Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter|W.Hochst.]]</small>\n*''Foetataxus taxifolia'' <small>(Arn.) [[K.Koch]]</small>\n*''Tumion taxifolium'' <small>(Arn.) [[Edward Lee Greene|Greene]]</small>\n*''Torreya montana'' <small>[[Hort.]]</small>\n*''Foetataxus montana'' <small>J.Nelson, [[nom. illegit.]]</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=PoWO>{{cite web |url=http://powo.science.kew.org/taxon/264000-1 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=Plants of the World Online |publisher=Board of Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Henkel1865>{{cite book |last=Henkel |first=Johann Baptist |author-link=:de:Johann Baptist Henkel |last2=Hochstetter |first2=Wilhelm Christian |author-link2=:de:Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter |date=1865 |title=Synopsis der nadelh\u00f6lzer, deren charakteristischen merkmale nebst andeutungen \u00fcber ihre cultur und ausdauer in Deutschlands klima. |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/15220968 |location=Stuttgart |publisher=Verlag der J. G. Cottaschen Buchhandlung |page=367, 368 |language=German |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.15349}}</ref><ref name=INPI4>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/?q=Taxus%20montana |title=''Taxus montana'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Nelson1866>{{cite book |last=Nelson |first=John (under the pseudonym Johannes Senilis) |date=1866 |title=Pinaceae: being a handbook of the firs and pines |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/45263307 |location=London |publisher=Hatchard and co. |page=167, 168 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.84872}}</ref><ref name=FlorPlAtl>{{cite web |url=https://florida.plantatlas.usf.edu/Plant.aspx?id=2330 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' - Species Page |last=Wunderlin |first=Richard P. |last2=Hansen |first2=Bruce F. |last3=Franck |first3=Alan R. |last4=Essig |first4=F. B. |date=17 March 2020 |website=ISB  Atlas of Florida Plants |publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany, University of South Florida, Tampa |access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Torreya taxifolia''''', commonly known as the '''Florida nutmeg''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993>{{cite report |author=Esser, Lora L. |date=1993 |title=''Torreya taxifolia''. In: Fire Effects Information System |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/database/feis/plants/tree/tortax/all.html |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Forest Service, Rocky Mountain Research Station, Fire Sciences Laboratory |page= |docket= |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=PLANTS>{{PLANTS |id=TOTA |taxon=Torreya taxifolia |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> '''Florida torreya''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA>{{cite book |last=Hils |first=Matthew H. |date=1993 |chapter=''Torreya taxifolia'' in Taxaceae Gray |chapter-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=220013607 |title=Flora of North America, Vol. 2: Pteridophytes and Gymnosperms |url=http://www.efloras.org/volume_page.aspx?volume_id=1002&flora_id=1 |location=New York and Oxford |publisher=Flora of North America Association |page= |isbn=}} see also: [http://www.efloras.org/object_page.aspx?object_id=5426&flora_id=1 RangeMap]</ref><ref name=Coile1998>{{cite book |last=Coile |first=Nancy C. |date=1998 |title=Notes on Florida's endangered and threatened plants |url=https://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00000172/00001/61x |location=Gainesville |publisher=Florida Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services, Division of Plant Industry |page=55 |isbn=}}</ref><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon>{{Cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823033709/http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/ASP/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=4295 |title=National Collection of Imperilled Plants (Center for Plant Conservation) |last=Kadis |first=Irina |date=18 June 2008 |accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Earle2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.conifers.org/ta/Torreya_taxifolia.php |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |last=Earle |first=Christopher J. |date=17 January 2020 |website=The Gymnosperm Database |publisher=Christopher J. Earle |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Alfieri1967>{{cite journal |last=Alfieri |first=S. A., Jr. |last2=Martinez |first2=A. P. |last3=Wehlburg |first3=C. |date=1967 |title=Stem and needle blight of Florida Torreya, ''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/58f7/4e704ed48844a26d41558b8205dad66514f6.pdf |journal=Proceedings of the Florida State Horticultural Society |volume=80 |issue= |pages=428-431 |doi= |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Smith2010>{{cite report |last=Smith |first=Jason Andrew |last2=Trulock |first2=Aaron |date=November 2010 |title=The Decline of Florida Torreya: An Endemic Conifer on the Edge of Extinction |url=https://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/fr338 |publisher=School of Forest Resources and Conservation, UF/IFAS Extension, University of Florida |page= |docket=FOR276 |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Alfieri1987>{{cite report |last=Alfieri |first=S. A. |last2=Schoulties |first2=C. L. |last3=Langdon |first3=K. R. |last4=El-Gholl |first4=Nabih Elias |date=January 1987 |title=Leaf and stem disease of ''Torreya taxifolia'' in Florida |url=https://www.fdacs.gov/content/download/11297/file/pp291.pdf |work=Plant Pathology Circular |publisher=Bureau of Plant Pathology, Florida Department Agriculture & Consumer Services |pages=1\u20144 |docket=291 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> '''gopher wood'''<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> or '''stinking-cedar'''<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> is an [[endangered]] tree of the yew [[Family (biology)|family]], [[Taxaceae]],<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> found in the [[Southeastern United States]], at the state border region of northern [[Florida]] and southwestern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=iucn2010/>\n\n''T. taxifolia'' became one of the first federally listed endangered plant species in the United States in 1984;<ref name=FNA/><ref name=USFWS1984>U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service. 1984. [http://ecos.fws.gov/docs/federal_register/fr789.pdf ''Federal Register'' (pdf)]</ref> the [[IUCN]] has listed the species as [[critically endangered]] since 1998.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=iucn2000>{{Cite iucn |author=Conifer Specialist Group 2000 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |volume=2000 |page=e.T30968A9585792 |date=2000 |doi= |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> In 2010 98% of the mature trees of the species were believed to be have been destroyed due to a poorly understood fungal blight as well as inundation due to dams and destruction by [[White-tailed deer|deer]] using trees as [[antler]] rubbing posts.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1821 the United States had managed to [[Adams\u2013On\u00eds Treaty|conquer]] the [[Florida Territory]] from [[Spain]] after years of surreptitiously trying to [[Republic of East Florida|usurp Spanish rule]], and begun the process of [[Seminole Wars|ethnically cleansing the land of its previous inhabitants]]. Plantation owners and their stocks of Negro slaves had began to move south to colonise and exploit the new land. One among them was the patriarch of the wealthy Croom family, who in 1826 purchased land around the town of [[Tallahassee]]. When he died in 1829, his two sons inherited his holdings and resolved to invest further in the region, buying up or leasing numerous plantations and eventually becoming the largest landowners in the area. They had all of their slaves shipped from their North Carolina plantations to labour at clearing the land, cultivating maize and cotton, and building [[Goodwood Plantation|giant mansions]] for their slave-masters. One of the two sons was Hardy Bryan Croom, who besides having studied law, being state senator in North Carolina since his early thirties, and his duties running the family and managing his properties, devoted some time to exploring the sciences.<ref name=McCormick2014>{{cite web |url=http://herbarium.unc.edu/Collectors/Croom_HB.htm |title=Hardy Bryan Croom |last=McCormick |first=Carol Ann |date=4 January 2014 |website=Collectors of the UNC Herbarium |publisher=University of North Carolina Herbarium |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Flowers1979>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/croom-hardy-bryan |title=Croom, Hardy Bryan |last=Flowers |first=John Baxton, III |date=1979 |website=Dictionary of North Carolina Biography |publisher=University of North Carolina Press |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Croom2005>{{cite web |url=http://www.johncroom.com/croopa19.htm |title=Hardy Bryan Croom |last=Croom |first=John H. |date=19 December 2005 |website=Croom Families and Other Related Surnames |publisher=John H. Croom |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Conrad2012>{{cite magazine |last=Conrad |first=Gibby |date=25 June 2012 |title=The life and death of Hardy Croom, first owner of Goodwood Plantation |url=https://www.tallahasseemagazine.com/the-life-and-death-of-hardy-croom-first-owner-of-goodwood-plantation/ |magazine=Tallahassee Magazine |location=Tallahassee |publisher=Rowland Publishing |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Among other scientific interests,<ref name=Croom2005/> he describes himself as fond of [[botany]], had assembled a small personal [[herbarium]]<ref name=Croom1834/> and posthumously authored a [[monograph]] on the [[carnivorous]] plant genus ''[[Sarracenia]]''.<ref name=Croom2005/>\n\nEast across the [[Apalachicola River|Apalache River]] from the first estate of his brother Bryan Croom in [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden]], who had acquired it in 1826 and coined it 'Rocky Comfort',<ref name=Croom2005/><ref name=Conrad2012/> (another source maintains Hardy Bryan Croom leased the property in 1832), he noted that the flora was quite unique compared to elsewhere in the Tallahassee region,<ref name=Conrad2012/> and sent specimens to the herbaria in the north from 1833,<ref name=McCormick2014/><ref name=Nuttall1849>{{cite book |last=Nuttall |first=Thomas |author-link=Thomas Nuttall |date=1849 |title=The North American sylva; or, A description of the forest trees of the United States, Canada and Nova Scotia |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433006568038&view=1up&seq=217 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Smith & Wistar |volume=3 |page=91, 92 |doi=}}</ref> and corresponded with the botanist [[John Torrey]] about the plants here from 1834 onwards.<ref name=Croom1834>{{cite book |last=Croom |first=Hardy Bryan |date=1834 |title=Hardy Bryan Croom and John Torrey correspondence, 1834-1837 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53333549 |location=New York |publisher=New York Botanical Garden Archives |page= |doi=}}</ref> Among the [[:wikt:exsiccata|exsiccata]] he sent north in 1833 were samples of a type of yew,<ref name=McCormick2014/> which in his 1834 first letter of reply to an inquiring Torrey he describes as having \"little doubt\" was the ''[[Taxus baccata]]'', the common yew of Europe. His description of the red berries appears to confuse this tree with another rare, local and hitherto undescribed species, [[Taxus floridana|''T. floridana'']].<ref name=Croom1834/>\n\nTorrey realised that Croom was quite mistaken, and that the specimens represented a species new to science.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Croom and his entire family drowned in a shipwreck off the coast of North Carolina in 1837.<ref name=McCormick2014/><ref name=Flowers1979/><ref name=Croom2005/><ref name=Conrad2012/> The novel species was eventually [[Species description|described]] by [[George Arnott Walker Arnott]] in April 1838 from specimens sent to Torrey and collected in Florida by Croom.<ref name=Nuttall1849/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/264000-1 |title=''Torreya taxifolia'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe species was moved to the [[Synonym (taxonomy)|junior synonym]] ''Caryotaxus taxifolia'' in 1865 by {{ill|Johann Baptist Henkel|de}} and {{ill|Wilhelm Christian Hochstetter|de}} in their monograph on the conifers of the world, ''Synopsis der Nadelh\u00f6lzer''.<!--Note: incorrect authority citation Index Kewensis, PoWO, etc.--><ref name=Henkel1865/> In 1873 [[Karl Koch (botanist)|Karl Heinrich Emil Koch]] moved the species to ''Foetataxus taxifolia''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/262078-1 |title=''Foetataxus taxifolia'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In 1891 [[Edward Lee Greene]] validated [[Constantine Samuel Rafinesque-Schmaltz]]'s [[generic epithet]] ''Tumion'' and erroneously moved this species there as ''Tumion taxifolium''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/258971-2 |title=''Tumion taxifolium'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/11722-1 |title=''Tumion'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn [[Thomas Nuttall]]'s entry about ''Torreya taxifolia'' in his book about American trees, which was published in 1849 although it had been for the most part completed in 1841, he relates that in the correspondence Torrey had sent him, mention had been made of specimens of another species of taxoid tree which had been sent to him by Croom from the same region. To this plant Nuttall \"doubtfully attaches the name\" ''Taxus montana'', somewhat of a [[nomen nudum]], because Nuttall never actually described the plant besides quoting a summary description from Torrey's letter to him. Nuttall is doubtful about the [[taxon]], because according to him it seems \"scarcely distinct\" from [[Taxus brevifolia|''T. brevifolia'']] of the [[Pacific Northwest]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Following the publication of this work, however, he was attributed as the author of this scientific name.<ref name=Henkel1865/><ref name=INPI4/> By 1865 this name was misapplied to ''Torreya taxifolia'' under the name ''Torreya montana''. Henkel and Hochstetter synonymised this taxon with ''T. taxifolia'' in their work mentioned above.<ref name=Henkel1865/> According to the [[Index Kewensis]] this was in error; the name ''Taxus montana'' had actually already been given to a species, now ''[[Prumnopitys montana]]'', described (validated, in fact) in 1806 by [[Carl Ludwig Willdenow]] from specimens collected by [[Alexander von Humboldt]] and [[Aim\u00e9 Bonpland]] on their famous scientific exploration of the Americas, and Nuttall had in fact referred to Willdenow's species.<ref name=INPI4/> [[John Nelson (horticulturist)|John Nelson]], in his more utilitarian as opposed to scientific 1866 horticultural handbook of firs and pines for growing in Britain, introduced the name ''Foetataxus montana'' to write about ''Torreya taxifolia'', apparently unaware of the German publication the previous year.<ref name=Nelson1866/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipni.org/n/262075-1 |title=''Foetataxus montana'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2020 |website=International Plant Names Index |publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In fact, all these sources were wrong, for Nuttall states that he found a newer specimen of Croom's, of the same taxon, in the Herbarium of the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia]] labelled as ''Taxus floridana''!<ref name=Nuttall1849/> Despite that the original synonymy with ''T. floridana'', all these names are still maintained in the synonymy of ''Torreya taxifolia'' in some modern databases as of 2020.<ref name=PoWO/>\n\nThe [[University of North Carolina]] Herbarium has a single specimen, originally from the Jesup Herbarium of [[Dartmouth College]], sent hither by Croom from the \"Apalache River\" in 1833. Curiously, it was first labelled as \"''Taxus montana'' Willd.\", a South American tree, which was then later changed to ''[[Prumnopitys taxifolia|Podocarpus taxifolia]]'' from southern [[New Zealand]], and finally relabelled as ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=McCormick2014/> \n\n===Higher classification===\nIt is the [[type species]] of the genus ''[[Torreya]]''. The species, and the genus ''Torreya'' in general, has also been placed in the [[Family (biology)|botanical family]] [[Cephalotaxaceae]].<ref name=\"Christenhusz2011\">{{Cite journal |last1=Christenhusz |first1=J. M. M. |last2=Reveal |first2=J. L. |last3=Martin |first3=F. G. |last4=Robert |first4=R. M. |last5=Chase |first5=W. M. |title=Linear sequence, classification, synonymy, and bibliography of vascular plants: Lycophytes, ferns, gymnosperms and angiosperms |year=2011 |journal=Phytotaxa |volume=19 |pages=1\u2013134 |url=http://www.mapress.com/phytotaxa/content/2011/f/pt00019p070.pdf|doi=10.11646/phytotaxa.19.1.1 }}</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\nArnott commemorated Torrey in the generic epithet.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Nuttall1849/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> The [[etymology]] of the [[specific epithet]] is from Latin [[:wikt:taxus#Latin|''taxus'']], meaning 'yew', and [[:wikt:folium#Latin|''folium'']], meaning 'leaf': i.e., 'yew-leaved'.<ref name=Earle2020/><ref>{{cite book |last=Sch\u00fctt |first=Peter |last2=Weisgerber |first2=Horst |last3=Schuck |first3=Hans J. |last4=Lang |first4=K. J. |last5=Stimm |first5=B. |last6=Roloff |first6=A. |date=2004 |title=Lexikon der Nadelb\u00e4ume |url= |location=Hamburg |publisher=Nikol-Verlagsges.mbH |page= |language=German |isbn=3-933203-80-5}}</ref> Other species of ''Torreya'' have longer, less yew-like leaves, but this is not the reason that it was given this name, as the other species were described after this one.<ref name=Earle2020/>\n\n==Common names==\nIt is likely most often known locally by the [[common name]] '''stinking-cedar'''.<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> Another local name used is '''gopher wood'''.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> Nuttall, writing in the early 1840s, coins the name \"yew-leaved torreya\" for it, but describes that in the land where it grows in the 1830s, it was known as \"stinking cedar\", which he ascribes to the \"strong and peculiar odour\" of the timber, especially when it is \"bruised or burnt\". He also mentions the seed, covered in the aril, are approximately the size of a [[nutmeg]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> In 1865 the German botanists Henkel and Hochstetter note that the Americans called the tree \"stinking cedar\" and \"wild nutmeg\". They mention that the name \"nutmeg\" is derived from the bone-hard shelled and acorn-sized seeds, which are covered in an aril somewhat similar to that of true nutmeg. They also describe that when the leaves are crushed they exude a pungent and disagreeable odour, which is why the local Americans used the name \"stinking cedar\". They themselves call the plant \"''Torrey's Nuss-Eibe''\", which translates as \"Torrey's nut-yew\" in English.<ref name=Henkel1865/> According to the gardening writer Nelson in 1866, ''Torreya'' species in general were known as \"stinking cedars\" or \"stinking nutmegs\" by the locals, though he himself recommended the name \"strong-odoured yew\" as preferred for British use. This specific species was called \"stinking cedar\" by the Americans according to him, although he recommended the name \"mountain yew\" for Britain -this is a calque of the (incorrect) Latin name he was using, he was apparently unaware of the fact that this species grows almost at sea level and nowhere near any mountains!<ref name=Nelson1866/> In fact, of all species of ''Torreya'', it is only the species which is never found in mountainous areas.\n\n[[Image:T taxifolia.jpg|thumb|Seed cone]]\n\nAlthough the [[vernacular name]] '''Florida torreya''' was formally recommended by most conservation works and internet databases,<ref name=FlorPlAtl/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> this was changed to '''Florida nutmeg''' in the late 2010s.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=PLANTS/> Other names for this tree are '''savin''',<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''polecat wood''',<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''yew-leaved torreya''',<ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=Nuttall1849/> '''foetid yew''',<ref name=Alfieri1987/> '''stinking cedar''',<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=USBG>{{cite web |url=https://m.usbg.gov/plants/stinking-cedar |title=Stinking cedar |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher=United States Botanic Garden |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> '''mountain yew''' (Britain)<ref name=Nelson1866/> or '''stinking yew'''{{cn|date=March 2020}} (applied to the Californian species ''[[Torreya californica]]'').<ref name=Nelson1866/>\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:The North American sylva (Pl. CIX) (9150099237).jpg|thumb|Plate from Nuttall's ''The North American sylva'', published 1849. It is captioned: \"A branch of the male plant, natural size. ''a''. Male [[Catkin|amentum]]. ''b''. Back view of one of the [[stamen]]s magnified. ''c''. Female ament and [[ovule]], magnified. ''d''. Section of the ripe seed. ''e''. Germinating seed.\"<ref name=Nuttall1849/>]]\n\n''Torreya taxifolia'' is an [[evergreen]] [[tree]] that may reach heights of {{convert|18|m}} with an {{convert|80|cm}} diameter trunk,<ref name=FNA/> although it typically grew to {{convert|9|-|12|m|ft}} tall and {{convert|30|-|50|cm|in}} in diameter,<ref name=Esser1993/> and most stands today are composed of immature trees of less than {{convert|3|m}} tall.<ref name=iucn2000/> The crown is open and conical in overall shape,<ref name=FNA/> with whorled branches.<ref name=Coile1998/> These branches are spreading to slightly drooping. The bark of two-year old branches are coloured yellowish-green, yellowish-brown or grey.<ref name=FNA/> The young branchlets divide into threes.<ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\nThe stiff, needle-like [[leaf|leaves]] are sharp to the touch,<ref name=Coile1998/> {{convert|1.5|-|3.8|cm|in}} long<ref name=FNA/> and 3&nbsp;mm broad.{{cn|date=March 2020}} These are arranged in two ranks on the branches<ref name=Alfieri1967/> and are coloured glossy green above and light green below,<ref name=Coile1998/> with a very slightly sunken grayish stripe of [[stomata]] on either side of the midrib on the underside,<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/> and slightly round in transverse profile on the topside.<ref name=FNA/> The leaves have an unpleasant, strongly pungent, resinous odor when crushed.<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Coile1998/>\n\nIt is [[dioecious]], with separate male and female plants.<ref name=iucn2010/> The male ([[pollen]]) [[conifer cone|cones]] resemble those of a common yew, but are much larger and have [[imbricate]]d scales ([[bract]]s) at their base.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> They are 5\u20137&nbsp;mm long, grouped in lines along the underside of a shoot. The female ([[seed]]) cones are single or grouped two to five together on a short stem; minute at first, they mature in about 18 months to a [[drupe]]-like structure with the single large [[nut (fruit)|nut]]-like seed{{cn|date=March 2020}} surrounded by a fleshy covering called an [[aril]], {{convert|2.5|-|3.5|cm|in}} long including aril,<ref name=FNA/> about the size of a nutmeg.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> The aril is [[:wikt:glaucous|glaucous]] and coloured dark green and streaked with purple at full maturity in the fall.<ref name=FNA/> Unlike true yews, in which the aril forms a \"cup\" around the seed, in this plant the aril completely encloses the seed, leaving only a minute perforation at the end. The aril is fleshy in consistency, like a fruit.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> When the aril is removed, the seed bears a striking resemblance to a large acorn.<ref name=Henkel1865/><ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[Image:Torreya taxifolia foliage.jpg|thumb|Foilage]]\n\n''Torreya taxifolia'' is restricted to [[limestone]] bluffs and [[ravine]]s along the east bank of the [[Apalachicola River]] in the central part of the northern [[Florida Panhandle]] and immediately adjacent southernmost [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=iucn2010/> near the town of [[Chattahoochee, Florida]];<ref name=Alfieri1987/> there is also a small colony west of the Apalachicola at Dog Pond in [[Jackson County, Florida|Jackson County]].<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Schwartz1993>{{cite journal |last=Schwartz |first=Mark William |last2=Hermann |first2=Sharon M. |date=July 1993 |title=The Continuing Population Decline of ''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn. |url= |journal=Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club |volume=120 |issue=3 |pages=275-286 |doi=10.2307/2996992}}</ref> It grows along the Apalachicola River just south of the confluence of the [[Chattahoochee River]] and the [[Flint River (Georgia)|Flint River]], which reach northwards through [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]] and [[Atlanta]] to drain the southern [[Blue Ridge Mountains]], a subrange of the [[Appalachian Mountains]].<ref name=Nuttall1849/> It only occurs in the Florida counties of [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden]], Jackson and [[Liberty County, Florida|Liberty]], and extends one mile into [[Decatur County, Georgia]]<ref name=Esser1993/> (another source states the northernmost wild individual currently growing in Georgia is within {{convert|200|m|ft}} of the Florida state line). The outlying population west of the Apalachicola, in Jackson County, has always been small: In 1938 H. Kurz reported it to be restricted to one stand with a few trees,<ref name=Schwartz2000>{{cite journal |last=Schwartz |first=Mark William |last2=Hermann |first2=Sharon M. |last3=Van Mantgem |first3=Philip J. |date=August 2000 |title=Estimating the magnitude of decline of the Florida torreya (''Torreya taxifolia'' Arn.) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261805791 |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=77-84 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(00)00008-2 |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> in 1974 this was reported as consisting of 60 trees,<ref name=Esser1993/> and in 1989 Mark William Schwartz and R. Nicholson reported it to consist of five trees.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThe area in which it naturally occurs is {{convert|203|km2|acres}}, stretching {{convert|35|km|miles}} along the Apalachicola River.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThere is a small introduced population on the Biltmore Estate in [[Asheville, North Carolina]], where it was planted as an [[ornamental plant]].<ref name=Esser1993/>\n\n===Prehistoric distribution===\nA number of sources state that this species has been recorded from fossils which suggest that at one time it grew over much of the eastern United States and that it has existed for 165 million years;<ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=USBG/> this is incorrect.<ref name=Barlow2015>{{cite report |last=Barlow |first=Connie |date=August 2015 |title=Paleoecology and the Assisted Migration Debate: Why a Deep-Time Perspective is Vital (''Torreya taxifolia'' as exemplar) |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/288671815 |publisher=Torreya Guardians |page=1\u201411 |doi=10.13140/RG.2.1.4299.0166 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Only two fossil examples are known of ''Torreya'' in eastern North America. The first was a species with dense, spirally arranged leaves described as [[Torreya caroliniana|''Tunion carolinianum'']] by [[Edward W. Berry]] in 1908 from the Mid-[[Cretaceous]] of North Carolina,<ref name=Berry1908>{{cite journal |last=Berry |first=Edward Wilber |date=1 May 1908 |title=A Mid-Cretaceous species of ''Torreya''; ''Tunion carolinianum'' sp. nov. |url=https://zenodo.org/record/1662627 |journal=American Journal of Science |volume=25 |issue=149 |pages=382\u2014386 |doi=10.2475/ajs.s4-25.149.382 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> the second is only known from a single piece of fossilised wood from the [[Upper Cretaceous]], also from North Carolina, which has been described as ''[[Torreya antiqua]]''.<ref name=Boeshore1936>{{cite journal |last=Boeshore |first=Irwin |last2=Gray |first2=William D. |date=1 October 1936 |title=An Upper Cretaceous Wood: ''Torreya antiqua'' |url= |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=23 |issue=8 |pages=524-528 |doi=10.1002/j.1537-2197.1936.tb09019.x}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nIt grows at altitudes of {{convert|15|-|30|m|ft}}, mostly on wooded ravines, bluffs and steep,<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=FNA/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> north-facing slopes.<ref name=iucn2010/> These ravines have nearly permanent seeps. It also occurs in the bottoms of ravines and adjacent floodplains.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> It grows in the shade under the canopy of larger trees.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The soils of this region are [[:wikt:calcareous|calcareous]],<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Nuttall1849/> moist, dark-coloured, sandy loams.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/>\n\nIt occurs in two types of habitats restricted to the river drainage, an oak-[[tupelo]]-cypress forest or an oak-pine forest.<ref name=Esser1993/> These forests are mostly [[deciduous]], but evergreen hardwoods and conifers are also common.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> R. M. Harper, who travelled throughout northern Florida by horse and train to document the compositions of various forests, stated in 1914 that the most frequent species in the Apalachicola ravines were ''[[Magnolia grandiflora]]'' (9.5%), spruce pine (''[[Pinus glabra]]'', 5.6%, American beech (''[[Fagus grandifolia]]'', 4.1%) and the understory ''Torreya taxifolia'' (4.0%) and ''Ilex opaca'' (3.5%).<ref name=Schwartz2000/> According to the IUCN the large trees in this habitat are ''[[Fagus grandifolia]]'', tulip tree (''[[Liriodendron tulipifera]]''), [[Acer floridanum|''Acer barbatum'']], sweetgum (''[[Liquidambar styraciflua]]''), white oak (''[[Quercus alba]]''), and occasionally loblolly pine (''[[Pinus taeda]]'') and ''[[Pinus glabra]]''.<ref name=iucn2010/> [[Magnolia]]s also grow in these woods.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Often these woods are hung with vines such as ''[[Smilax]]'' species and crossvine (''[[Bignonia capreolata]]'').<ref name=iucn2010/> Another rare conifer, the Florida yew (''[[Taxus floridana]]''), occasionally grows with ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Vaughan2001>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040725080037/http://www.hort.agri.umn.edu:80/h5015/rrr.htm |title=Restoration of longleaf pine and wiregrass at the Apalachicola Bluffs Preserve (Florida) |last=Vaughan |first=Elizabeth |date=2001 |website=Volume 7- Fall 2001: Lessons Learned From Long-Term Restorations. Restoration and Reclamation Review, Student On-Line Journal (Hort 5015/5071) |publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> A rare salamander found in these ravines is ''[[Desmognathus apalachicolae]]''. The ravines boast the southernmost parts of the ranges of a number of more northern species such as the plants ''[[Hydrangea quercifolia]]'', ''[[Epigaea repens]]'' and ''[[Kalmia latifolia]]'' and the copperhead snake ''[[Agkistrodon contortrix]]''.<ref name=Vaughan2001/> Upland around these woodlands are [[flatwoods]], which are a longleaf pine/wiregrass (''[[Pinus palustris]]''/''[[Aristida stricta]]'') sandhill plant community.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Vaughan2001/> It is uncommon in its native habitats, with individuals spaced far apart.<ref name=Esser1993/>\n\nVarious animals eat the seeds.<ref name=Esser1993/> Rodents favour the seeds.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Squirrels apparently remove the seeds, which they eat, from the arils, which they do not eat, and often store them in [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|caches]] for the winter, where they may sprout into new trees.<ref name=Barlow2001>{{Cite magazine |last=Barlow |first=Connie |date=2001 |title=Anachronistic Fruits and the Ghosts Who Haunt Them |url=http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/618.pdf |magazine=Arnoldia |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=19-21 |location=Boston, Massachusetts |publisher=Arnold Arboretum of Harvard University |accessdate=2014-07-26}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Torreya Park Apalachicola River pano02.jpg|thumb|250px|View of [[Apalachicola River]] at [[Torreya State Park]]]]\n\nIn a 2001 newsletter, the writer Connie Barlow suggested that ''T. taxifolia'' may be an [[evolutionary anachronism]] similar to the Osage orange (''[[Maclura pomifera]]'') and Kentucky coffeetree (''[[Gymnocladus dioicus]]''), which are thought to have been dispersed by a now-extinct animal. She made this suggestion based on the fact that this species is rare, that it grew well in the cooler temperatures of [[North Carolina]], and her belief that the species was only found on the east bank of the Apalachicola and was unable to disperse to the west bank with the animals she thought might be the main dispersal agents today, squirrels. She theorised than during the [[Eemian|last interglacial]] (the geologically short periods between [[ice age]]s) and the proceeding ones, the species grew further north. According to her theories, because there might have been an unknown and now extinct animal in the past which was better suited to eat and defecate the seeds, or otherwise move the seeds, the species was now \"stuck\" behind the Apalachicola which served as a refuge habitat for a [[Relict (biology)|relict population]] during the long periods of glacial conditions which characterised the [[Pleistocene]]. She further supposed that because the arils contain [[terpene]]s which are usually toxic for mammals, and the seed's shell is so thin that mammal molars would crush the seeds, that the purported extinct animal might not be a mammal and instead suggested some unknown species of large [[tortoise]] as the extinct ecological partner.<ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n==Uses==\nIt is has been far too rare to harvest commercially since the 1950s, but it has a beautiful, yellow-coloured, close-grained wood. The timber is lightweight, hard, strong and highly durable.<ref name=Esser1993/> In the 19th century, the tree was harvested for wood that was used as fence posts,<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> shingles,<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> cabinets,<ref name=Esser1993/> [[Christmas tree]]s,<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Esser1993/> firewood,<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> and as a fuel for riverboats on the [[Apalachicola River]].<ref name=iucn2010/> Fences made of this wood in the 1910s were still good in the 1970s.<ref name=Esser1993/> In the 1830s it was locally abundant enough for the trees to be harvested to be sawn into planks, which were much used in the construction of the village of [[Aspalaga Landing]]. In this era it was also recommended as making excellent posts for fencing, not being liable to attack by insects.<ref name=Nuttall1849/>\n\nWhen the trunks are damaged, the trees yield a small quantity of pasty, viscous, blood-red [[turpentine]], which can be dissolved in alcohol, but has a very powerful and unpleasant odour.<ref name=Nuttall1849/> \n\n===Cultivation===\nThe tree is well-represented in cultivation, and is widely planted outside of its native range as an ornamental, and is found in private gardens, [[arboretum|arboreta]] and botanical gardens.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/>\n\nIt was first imported to grow in Europe in 1840. Large trees were to be found in [[Germany]] by the 1860s.<ref name=Henkel1865/> It is tolerably hardy, but grows very slowly in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], and as such was only recommended for collectors.<ref name=Nelson1866/>\n\nIt has occasionally been planted as a landscape tree around [[Tallahassee]], and one such specimen in [[Lee, Florida]] has achieved {{convert|30|ft}}.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> Some large specimens are grown elsewhere in botanical gardens. The [[champion tree]] of the species is in a private garden in [[Norlina, North Carolina]], having a height of {{convert|45|ft}}, a trunk diameter of {{convert|88|cm}} [[Diameter at breast height|dbh]] and a canopy width of {{convert|40|ft}} in 1996.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> It has been said to endure winter temperatures of {{convert|-31|C}} in North Carolina without much problem.<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n===Propagation===\nCuttings of ''Torreya'' shoot-tips often show fungal contamination. Experimental studies with weekly sprayed applications of a combinations of [[Systemic pesticide|systemic]] [[fungicide]]s, such as [[thiophanate-methyl]] combined with [[zinc]] and [[Maneb]] or [[thiabendazole]], were able to eliminate the fungi from stock plants after four weeks, although these preparations were not US government approved as of 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> \n\nTissue culture methods of propagation were being investigated as of 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\n==Conservation==\nThe first person to notice that the trees were dying was the forester L. T. Nieland in 1938, although he never wrote a formal paper about it. In the same year Kurz made a detailed study of the ecology of species and mentioned that there was no danger to the species vanishing from its habitat if lumbering would cease.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> In 1954 Kurz and R. K. Godfrey surveyed the population and noticed no symptoms of decline. However, in 1962 Godfrey and Kurz, having surveyed the species again, reported that the natural stands of this species, which was historically never widely distributed, were dying off and extinction seemed assured, if not already accomplished.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962>{{cite journal |last=Godfrey |first=R. K. |last2=Kurz |first2=H. |date=1962 |title=The Florida Torreya destined for extinction |url= |journal=Science |volume=136 |pages=900-902 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> By 1962, only non-reproductive sprouts regrowing from the top-killed stumps remained in the wild,<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962/> a situation which has persisted throughout the 20th century.<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> They attributed this to deforestation due to the lumber trade.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=GodfreyKurz1962/> However, samples of the afflicted trees were sent to the [[University of Florida]], where Erdman West suggested the decline appeared due to a fungal blight of some kind. In a 1967 article S. A. Alfieri Jr. ''et al''. of the [[Florida Department of Agriculture]] presented their research of the phenomenon. The disease presents itself as a small, yellowish spot on the needles (leaves) -one or more per leaf, which soon spreads throughout the leaf until it dies, turns brown and falls off. Subsequently the disease spreads into the twig, and all of the needles fall off, leaving only a tuft of new growth at the tip. The disease spreads in stages, first affecting portions, later the entire tree. Severely infected trees eventually loose most of their needles and twigs. Fungal fruiting structures grow on wholly necrotic tissue on the underside of the leaves, twigs and buds. In some cases, the stems of affected or dead trees also showed fungal [[canker]]. Young seedlings are also affected, but less severely than older trees. Trees growing in the shade are more affected than those in full sunlight.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> \n\nIn 1985 the [[phytopathologist]] Nabih Elias El-Gholl, also of the Florida Department of Agriculture, was able to prove that there were at least two pathogens involved; the leaf-spot disease presented as light greyish-green spots, which later became tan-coloured, and were up to 8.4mm long and as wide as the needle, with brown, irregularly-shaped, 2.4mm long \u00d7 2mm wide, necrotic centres and were able to infect the plants in the absence of wounds within three days of inoculation. Initially only a few spots, maximally four, developed per plant. After some two weeks the infected needles died and fell off -by this time the undersides had developed spore structures,<ref name=El-Gholl1985>{{cite journal |last=El-Gholl |first=Nabih Elias |date=1985 |title=''Fusarium lateritium'' Causing Needle Spots on ''Torreya taxifolia'' in Florida |url=https://www.apsnet.org/publications/PlantDisease/BackIssues/Documents/1985Abstracts/PD_69_905a.htm |journal=Plant Disease |volume=69 |pages=905 |doi=10.1094/PD-69-905a |access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> which were primarily found along the two grey bands of stomata, but may also occur on the twigs.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nThe canker disease presents as elongated [[fusiform]] swellings on the stems which eventually may break open. They are often found at the base of the trees.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nIn 1993 Schwartz, who has spent much of his career researching the conservation of this species, and Sharon M. Hermann, reported on the progression of the disease. They monitored a census population of some 100 trees for four years, in this time 10% died, mostly the smaller individuals. Most plants consisted of multi-stemmed, regenerating stumps; the mean length of the longest stems were less than one meter. Less than half of the plants showed any growth in length during these four years, and 32% lost their primary stem, which meant the mean size of individuals within the population was decreasing. Death was not strongly related to specific location or if the plants showed disease symptoms, although stem mortality was higher with trees showing a higher severity of foliar pathogens.<ref name=Schwartz1993/> In 2000 Schwartz ''et al''. reported that despite Godfrey and Kurz's 1962 prediction, a small population size, continued population losses, and no known seed production for decades, extinction of ''T. taxifolia'' had not yet occurred, and although the population would likely steadily decline, it was unlikely to go extinct within the next 50 years.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\n===Status===\nThis was one of the first federally listed {{C|Endangered flora of the United States|endangered plant species in the United States}} in 1984 (Federal Register 1/23/84).<ref name=FNA/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref name=USFWS1984/> It is one of only two species of conifer protected under the [[Endangered Species Act]].<ref name=Earle2020/> It was listed as \"[[threatened species|threatened]]\" within the state of Florida by 1987 (Florida Statutes Section 581.185),<ref name=Alfieri1987/> again in 1994 by the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission,<ref name=Esser1993/> and in 1998 the status in Florida was changed to \"[[endangered]]\".<ref name=PLANTS/><ref name=Coile1998/> In 2002 it was added to the list of \"endangered\" plants of Georgia.<ref name=PLANTS/><ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> It has been a \"[[critically endangered]]\" species on the [[IUCN Red List]] since 1998, in 2000 this was said to be due to estimated 98% decline in mature individuals since the early 1950s.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=iucn2000/>\n\n===Population===\nIn 2000 Schwartz and colleagues calculated that before the start of the decline, the original population of ''T. taxifolia'' may have been 300,000 between 650,000 plants, with 357,500 individual trees being the preferred estimate, based on a historic abundance of 14.2% of dominant ravine trees in 1914, or 30 trees/ha, and a historic distribution of some {{convert|203|km2|acres}}.<ref name=Schwartz2000/> Only 27 trees were counted in Georgia in 1981.<ref name=iucn2000/> In 1993 Schwartz estimated that there were only 1500 trees in the wild.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Schwartz1993/> Based on the extrapolation of a survey of five stands of the 2000 survey, attenuated with assumptions that these stands were the most dense, Schwartz ''et al''. calculated the population in its native habitat to be between 500 and 4,000 individuals, with none capable of reproduction. The most likely population was calculated to be 1,361 individuals, not including the population west of the Apalachicola. Using their estimate of the pre-decline population, they thus calculated a minimum 98.5% decline in population over the last 50 years.<ref name=Schwartz2000/> The [[IUCN]] estimated that the population is 999 mature individuals in its native habitat (although, confusingly, it also states the population to consist of between 500 and 600 trees elsewhere in the assessment), of which less than ten were known to produce male or female cones.<ref name=iucn2010/> It stated that the population continued to decrease,<ref name=iucn2010/> although the decline may be reversible should the causes of infection be better understood.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Schwartz2000/> IUCN population viability analyses indicate that [[extinction]] within its native range is inevitable.<ref name=iucn2010/>\n\nThe IUCN stated the total [[extent of occurrence]] is estimated to be about {{convert|200|km2|acres}},<ref name=iucn2010/> this is the same as the historical distribution. Schwartz states that these has been no logging in its habitat since the 1950s and that this species has experienced no [[habitat loss]]: the vast majority of the original ravine forest habitat remains.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\n===Threats===\nThe most significant current threat to the species is the continued reproductive failure associated with [[fungal]] pathogens.<ref name=iucn2010/><ref name=Smith2010/> Individuals do not reach reproductive size before being top-killed.<ref name=iucn2010/> Almost no plants are able to reach a reproductive size, and where seeds do form, these are soft, crumbly and not viable.<ref name=Esser1993/> Up to ten species of fungi have been found growing in infected ''Torreya taxifolia''.<ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/><ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date= |title=''Fusarium torreyae'' sp nov., a pathogen causing canker disease of Florida torreya (''Torreya taxifolia''), a critically endangered conifer restricted to northern Florida and southwestern Georgia |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232705140 |journal= |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlfieri ''et al''. were able to [[Isolate (biology)|isolate]] five species of fungi in 1967 from the stems and leaves, but failed to isolate any of the fungi from the cankered stems on the media they were using, [[potato dextrose agar]]. They reported that the disease appeared to implicate species tentatively identified as ''[[Physalospora]]'' and ''[[Macrophoma]]'', but also isolated the fungi ''[[Rhizoctonia solani]]'', ''[[Sclerotium rolfsii]]'' and a ''[[Sphaeropsis]]'' species from the infected tissue.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> They attempted to reproduce the infections by spraying the isolates, as well as pulverised [[Plant litter|stem and leaf litter]], on seedlings grown in greenhouses from unaffected ornamental trees in local parks, but their experiments failed to induce the disease in their seedlings.<ref name=Alfieri1967/> Nonetheless reports from 1975 and 1988 continued to identify the responsible fungi as these previous two species.<ref name=Esser1993/> In 1985 El-Gholl was finally able to prove [[Koch's postulates]] with ''[[Gibberella baccata]]'' (as ''[[Fusarium lateritium]]'', an [[Teleomorph, anamorph and holomorph|anamorph]] isolate) as the agent responsible for the leaf spot pathogen, but he was unable to replicate the disease causing the stem cankers.<ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=El-Gholl1985/><ref name=MycoBank>{{cite web |url=http://www.mycobank.org/Biolomics.aspx?Table=Mycobank&Rec=34922&Fields=All |title=''Gibberella baccata'' |last=Bensch |first=K. |date=2020 |website=MycoBank |publisher=International Mycological Association (IMA) and the Westerdijk Fungal Biodiversity Institute |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> In 1987 Alfieri ''et al''. reported on experiments with this fungus, as well as another two more species isolated from the infected plants, ''[[Xylocoremium flabelliforme]]'' (the anamorph state of ''[[Xylaria cubensis]]'') and the ''Macrophoma'' which they had re-identified as a ''[[Phyllosticta]]'' species, the anamorph form of ''[[Guignardia]]''. They were able to reproduce El-Gholl's results, but again failed to identify the canker producing agent, the other two isolates proved not to cause any disease.<ref name=Smith2010/><ref name=Alfieri1987/> In a 1996 article Lee ''et al''. mentioned that the [[endophyte]] they were studying, ''[[Pestalotiopsis microspora]]'' might be the cause of the decline of the species, because a strain they isolated produced a hitherto unknown [[cytotoxin]] they named \"[[torreyanic acid]]\", a [[Merosity|dimeric]] [[quinone]].<ref name=Lee1996>{{cite journal |last=Lee |first=Julie Chu-Li |last2=Strobel |first2=Gary A. |last3=Lobkovsky |first3=Emil |last4=Clardy |first4=Jon |date=17 May 1996 |title=Torreyanic Acid: A Selectively Cytotoxic Quinone Dimer from the Endophytic Fungus ''Pestalotiopsis microspora'' |journal=The Journal of Organic Chemistry |volume=61 |issue=10 |pages=3232\u20133233 |doi=10.1021/jo960471x}}</ref> ''P. microspora'' is a usually [[Commensalism|commensal]] fungus commonly found within the tissues of many plant species, and is only rarely a pathogen -in these cases it is an [[Opportunistic infection|opportunistic pathogen]].<ref name=Smith2010/> However, recent research has identified a previously unknown species of ''[[Fusarium]]'' may be the cause.<ref name=iucn2010/> \n\nBy 1987 the canker disease had spread to plants cultivated outside the native range such as in the [[University of Florida]] campus in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and in the [[Alfred B. Maclay Gardens State Park]] in Tallahassee.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> \n\nAccording to one older theory logging of shade trees may stress individuals of this species, which does not like being suddenly exposed to full sunlight, conducing infection.<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1967/><ref name=Smith2010/>\n\nAnother threat to the population is destruction by [[White-tailed deer|deer]].<ref name=iucn2010/> Deer preferentially select young trees of this species to rub their new antlers on, sometimes killing them. Feral pigs may also uproot and destroy seedlings.<ref name=Esser1993/> Another possible cause of the historical decline may be changes in the environment due to fire suppression, and changes in water tables linked to the construction of dams.<ref name=iucn2010/> Specifically, many trees were killed when the land was flooded<ref name=Esser1993/> in the construction of the [[Jim Woodruff Dam]] impounding [[Lake Seminole]].<ref name=USBG/>\n\nAccording to one writer, the population of the species may have been impacted by postglacial [[global warming]], as it may possibly be better adapted to the cooler climate found in Florida during the last [[ice age]]. It may not have been able to move north due to poor dispersal abilities. This is based on the fact that the introduced population on the Biltmore estate in North Carolina appears to be doing fine, and is even reproducing naturally -squirrels plant the seeds in the flower beds and these germinate.<ref name=Barlow2001/>\n\n===Actions===\n[[Fungicide]] treatment with [[Maneb]] has been shown to be remarkably effective, with plants showing renewed growth afterwards with little to no fungal infection. It has been applied since 1967,<ref name=Esser1993/><ref name=Alfieri1967/> but as of 1987 it is not specifically labelled for use in ''Torreya''.<ref name=Alfieri1987/>\n\nA theory perhaps first put forward in 1990 by Greg Seamon, land manager at the [[Apalachicola Bluffs and Ravines Preserve]], was that ''Torreya taxifolia'' may be somehow suffering from the suppression of fire in the upland longleaf pine-wiregrass sandhill ecosystems. However, after regular fires were again instituted in the 1990s in the preserve, this appeared not to have an effect, with the species experiencing an increased three percent annual mortality at the turn of the century.<ref name=Vaughan2001/>\n\nTwo years after declaring the species an endangered species, in 1986, the [[U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service]] published a recovery plan. The chief tactic was to produce a genetically diverse collection of trees for reproduction and reintroduction into the wild. Other priorities were to protect the habitat of remaining populations, and to study the disease and methods of [[Plant propagation|propagation]].<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/>\n\nPlants in general attract very little funding compared to [[vertebrate]]s, this tree is no different. The US federal government spent only $1,500 on conservation of the species in 1993, placing it 884th out of 926 endangered species. Schwartz ''et al''. stated that recovery is possible, but this will require a greater level of commitment and a dedicated increase in funding.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nSmall experiments by Schwartz and Hermann in the 1990s found that planting cuttings in the native habitat is possible. Schwartz ''et al''. recommended population augmentation by planting volunteers isolated by more than 100m from extant stands to reduce chance of contamination.<ref name=Schwartz2000/>\n\nThe tree is well-represented in cultivation, and is widely planted for conservation purposes outside of its native range.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> Plants outside of its historic native distribution are undamaged by fungal disease and produce viable seed.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Schwartz2000/> In Tallahassee for example, not far from the native range, a number of large trees had been grown for almost a century in the Alfred B. Maclay Gardens without problems and had been successfully propagated here since the 1960s,<ref name=Alfieri1967/> although the trees in this park became infected by the canker disease by 1987.<ref name=Alfieri1987/> It is found in [[arboretum|arboreta]], botanical gardens and elsewhere throughout the world.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=Earle2020/> In the [[Netherlands]], for example, it is grown in the [[Arboretum Trompenburg]], the {{ill|Arboretum Oudenbosch|nl}}, the [[Hortus Haren]], the [[Hortus Botanicus Amsterdam]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.botanischetuinen.nl/planten/plant/1641/torreya-taxifolia/ |title=Florida torreya |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Plantzoeker |publisher=Nederlandse Vereniging van Botanische Tuinen |language=Dutch |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> and the {{ill|Pinetum Blijdenstein|nl}}.<ref>{{cite report |authors=Stichting Pinetum Blijdenstein |date=July 2016 |title=Pinetum Blijdenstein \u2014 Beleidsplan 2016 \u2013 2020 v.1.0 |url=https://api1.ibabs.eu/publicdownload.aspx?site=hilversum&id=100131346 |publisher=Stichting Pinetum Blijdenstein |page=22 |language=Dutch |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States the [[Center for Plant Conservation]] maintains the species in its National Collection of Endangered Plants; the [[Arnold Arboretum]] of [[Harvard University]] is the primary custodian of this species.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The [[Atlanta Botanical Garden]] and the [[State Botanical Garden of Georgia]] are actively propagating the plant for conservation purposes. These are members of the Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance, which is protecting the species by growing seedlings and cuttings, and planting these both ''[[in situ]]'' and ''[[ex situ]]''.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/><ref name=USBG/><ref name=UGAbotGar>{{cite report |author= |date=April 2008 |title=GPCA Safeguarding Policy Statement - Policy Statement Regarding ''in situ'' and ''ex situ'' Plant Conservation Between Members of the Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance |url=https://botgarden.uga.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/GPCA-Safeguarding-Policy-Statement-.pdf |publisher=Georgia Plant Conservation Alliance |pages=1-10 |docket= |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Plants are also grown at the [[United States Botanic Garden]].<ref name=USBG/> \n\nIn her intriguing but somewhat unsubstantiated 2001 newsletter article Barlow synthesized her suppositions to suggest that the only way to conserve the species was for humans to engage in [[assisted migration]], transplanting across great distances. She noted that, in essence, humans are now the gardeners artificially preserving most isolated islands of \"wilderness\" amongst a sea of human development, if we like it or not.<ref name=Barlow2001/> In this she was not unique, in 1994 Foote and Jones had already written that the survival of this species was likely dependent upon cultivation in gardens.<ref name=Kadis2008CenPlCon/> The idea is that ''T. taxifolia'' for some reason was unable to migrate north from its \"ice age pocket refuge\" in northern Florida.<ref name=Fox2007>{{cite magazine |last=Fox |first=Douglas |date=January 2007 |title=When worlds collide |url=http://conservationmagazine.org/2008/07/when-worlds-collide/ |magazine=Conservation |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=28-34 |location= |publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> This inspired the formation of a group, Torreya Guardians, which are attempting to [[rewilding (conservation biology)|rewild]] ''Torreya taxifolia'' trees in cooler mountain areas in the southern [[Appalachians]] in an attempt to aid the species.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torreyaguardians.org/rewilding.html |title=Rewilding ''Torreya taxifolia''? |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=April 2015 |publisher=Torreya Guardians |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Some conservationists consider ''T. taxifolia'' as the lead candidate for assisted migration.<ref name=Fox2007/> This project has proved contentious.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Nijhuis |first=Michelle |date=May\u2013June 2008 |title=Taking Wildness in Hand: Rescuing Species |url=http://www.orionmagazine.org/index.php/articles/article/2966/ |magazine=Orion Magazine |pages=64\u201378 |location=Great Barrington, Massachusetts |publisher=The Orion Society |access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Protected areas===\nThe natural populations are largely [[protected area|protected]] within the [[Torreya State Park]]<ref name=Earle2020/><ref name=Alfieri1967/> and at the [[Nature Conservancy]]'s [[Apalachicola Bluffs and Ravines Preserve]] (first parcels purchased in 1982 to protect the ravines, before the species was officially listed as endangered).<ref name=Vaughan2001/>\n\n==References and external links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Reflist|refs=}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q595832}}\n\n[[Category:Torreya|taxifolia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Florida]]\n[[Category:Flora of Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Trees of the Southeastern United States]]\n[[Category:Apalachicola River|~]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered flora of the United States]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1838]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torreya_taxifolia"}
{"title_page": "Monika Bronicka", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish former sailor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name = Monika Bronicka\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| fullname = Monika Bronicka\n| nationality = {{POL}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|5|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Olsztyn]], Poland\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = {{height|m=1.68|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|66|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website = \n| country = \n| classes = [[Dinghy]]\n| club = [[Indykpol AZS Olsztyn|AZS UWM Olsztyn]]\n| coach = Mariusz Delgas\n| medaltemplates= \n| show-medals = yes\n}}\n\n'''Monika Bronicka''' (born 4 May 1977) is a Polish former sailor, who specialized in the [[Europe (dinghy)|Europe]] class.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Monika Bronicka|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/br/monika-bronicka-1.html|12 August 2018}}</ref> She was selected to compete for [[Poland]] in two editions of the Olympic Games (2000 and 2004), and also scored top fifteen placements in a major international regatta, spanning the World and European Championships.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monika Bronicka zako\u0144czy\u0142a karier\u0119!|trans-title=Monika Bronicka ends her career|language=pl|url=https://zagle.se.pl/zeglarstwo/monika-bronicka-zakonczya-kariere-aa-JS3U-hHB6-om6t.html|publisher=\u017bagle|date=23 June 2008|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>  Bronicka is a member of the sailing squad for [[Indykpol AZS Olsztyn|AZS UWM Olsztyn]], under the tutelage of her personal coach and eventual spouse Mariusz Delgas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Z Chwaszczyna na Antypody|trans-title=From Chwaszczyna to Antipodes|language=pl|url=https://radiogdansk.pl/audycje-rg/fabryka-reportazu/item/28011-z-chwaszczyna-na-antypody|publisher=Radio Gda\u0144sk|date=19 August 2015|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nBronicka made her Olympic debut in [[Sydney 2000]], finishing a credible fourteenth in the [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe|Europe]] class with a satisfying net grade of 95, but narrowly falling short from the top ten spot by a distant twelve-point deficit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sydney 2000: Sailing \u2013 Women's Europe Class|url=http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/2000/Masters/sa/SAresults.pdf|format=[[PDF]]|work=[[Sydney 2000]]|publisher=[[LA84 Foundation]]|page=105|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], Bronicka qualified for her second Polish team in the [[Sailing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe|Europe]] class by placing fourteenth and receiving a berth from the [[2003 ISAF Sailing World Championships|2003 ISAF World Championships]] in [[Cadiz, Spain|Cadiz]]. Unlike her previous Games, Bronicka could not be able to improve her Olympic feat with mediocre marks recorded throughout the eleven-race series, sitting her in twenty-first position with 162 net points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sailing: Women's Europe Class|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics_2004/sailing/results/3531748.stm|work=[[Athens 2004]]|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 August 2004|accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|www.bronicka.sails.pl/}} {{in lang|pl}}\n*{{World Sailing|39677|POLMB1}}\n*{{PKOl profile|189,bronicka-monika}}\n*{{IOC profile|monika-bronicka}}\n*{{Olympic Channel|monika-bronicka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bronicka, Monika}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Polish female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Poland]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe]]\n[[Category:People from Olsztyn]]\n\n\n{{Poland-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Polish former sailor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox sailor\n| name = Monika Bronicka\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| fullname = Monika Bronicka\n| nationality = {{POL}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|5|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Olsztyn]], Poland\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = {{height|m=1.68|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|66|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website = \n| country = \n| classes = [[Dinghy]]\n| club = [[Indykpol AZS Olsztyn|AZS UWM Olsztyn]]\n| coach = Mariusz Delgas\n| medaltemplates= \n| show_medals = yes\n}}\n\n'''Monika Bronicka''' (born 4 May 1977) is a Polish former sailor, who specialized in the [[Europe (dinghy)|Europe]] class.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Monika Bronicka|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/br/monika-bronicka-1.html|12 August 2018}}</ref> She was selected to compete for [[Poland]] in two editions of the Olympic Games (2000 and 2004), and also scored top fifteen placements in a major international regatta, spanning the World and European Championships.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monika Bronicka zako\u0144czy\u0142a karier\u0119!|trans-title=Monika Bronicka ends her career|language=pl|url=https://zagle.se.pl/zeglarstwo/monika-bronicka-zakonczya-kariere-aa-JS3U-hHB6-om6t.html|publisher=\u017bagle|date=23 June 2008|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>  Bronicka is a member of the sailing squad for [[Indykpol AZS Olsztyn|AZS UWM Olsztyn]], under the tutelage of her personal coach and eventual spouse Mariusz Delgas.<ref>{{cite news|title=Z Chwaszczyna na Antypody|trans-title=From Chwaszczyna to Antipodes|language=pl|url=https://radiogdansk.pl/audycje-rg/fabryka-reportazu/item/28011-z-chwaszczyna-na-antypody|publisher=Radio Gda\u0144sk|date=19 August 2015|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nBronicka made her Olympic debut in [[Sydney 2000]], finishing a credible fourteenth in the [[Sailing at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe|Europe]] class with a satisfying net grade of 95, but narrowly falling short from the top ten spot by a distant twelve-point deficit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sydney 2000: Sailing \u2013 Women's Europe Class|url=http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/2000/Masters/sa/SAresults.pdf|format=[[PDF]]|work=[[Sydney 2000]]|publisher=[[LA84 Foundation]]|page=105|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], Bronicka qualified for her second Polish team in the [[Sailing at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe|Europe]] class by placing fourteenth and receiving a berth from the [[2003 ISAF Sailing World Championships|2003 ISAF World Championships]] in [[Cadiz, Spain|Cadiz]]. Unlike her previous Games, Bronicka could not be able to improve her Olympic feat with mediocre marks recorded throughout the eleven-race series, sitting her in twenty-first position with 162 net points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sailing: Women's Europe Class|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics_2004/sailing/results/3531748.stm|work=[[Athens 2004]]|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 August 2004|accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|www.bronicka.sails.pl/}} {{in lang|pl}}\n*{{ISAF|id=POLMB1}}\n*[http://www.olimpijski.pl/pl/bio/189,bronicka-monika.html Polish Olympic Committee] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bronicka, Monika}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Polish female sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Poland]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Europe]]\n[[Category:People from Olsztyn]]\n\n\n{{Poland-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update World Sailing link, add Olympics link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monika_Bronicka"}
{"title_page": "James Rosenquist", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = James Rosenquist\n| image         = James_rosenquist1.jpg\n| caption       = Photo by: Russ Blaise 1988\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1933|11|29|}}\n| birth_place    = [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age |2017|03|31 |1933|11|29}}\n| death_place    = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| field         = Painting, [[printmaking]], drawing\n| training      = [[Minneapolis College of Art and Design]]<br>[[University of Minnesota]]<br>[[Art Students League of New York]]\n| movement      = [[Pop art]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Mary Lou Adams|1960|1975|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|Mimi Thompson|1987}}\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''James Rosenquist''' (November 29, 1933 \u2013 March 31, 2017) was an American artist and one of the proponents of the [[pop art]] movement. Drawing from his background working in sign painting, Rosenquist's pieces often explored the role of advertising and consumer culture in art and society, utilizing techniques he learned making commercial art to depict popular cultural icons and mundane everyday objects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com/artist/biography|title=Biography - Artist - James Rosenquist Studio|last=exhibit-e.com|website=www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> While his works have often been compared to those from other key figures of the pop art movement, such as [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Roy Lichtenstein]], Rosenquist's pieces were unique in the way that they often employed elements of surrealism using fragments of advertisements and cultural imagery to emphasize the overwhelming nature of ads.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theartstory.org/artist-rosenquist-james.htm|title=James Rosenquist Biography, Art, and Analysis of Works|work=The Art Story|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref> He was a 2001 inductee into the [[Florida Artists Hall of Fame]].<ref>[http://www.florida-arts.org/programs/ahf/displayArtist.cfm?member=31 James Rosenquist] Florida Artists Hall of Fame</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRosenquist was born on November 29, 1933, in [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]],<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> the only child of Louis and Ruth Rosenquist. His parents were amateur pilots of [[Swedes|Swedish]] descent who moved from town to town to look for work, finally settling in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. His mother, who was also a painter, encouraged her son to have an artistic interest. In junior high school, Rosenquist won a short-term scholarship to study at the [[Minneapolis College of Art and Design|Minneapolis School of Art]] and subsequently studied painting at the [[University of Minnesota]] from 1952 to 1954.  In 1955, at the age of 21, he moved to [[New York, New York|New York City]] on scholarship to study at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]], studying under painters such as [[Edwin Dickinson]] and [[George Grosz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist/|title=In the Studio: James Rosenquist|last=Kastner|first=Jeffrey|date=November 22, 2007|publisher=artinfo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080524084109/http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist/|archivedate=May 24, 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 21, 2008}}</ref> Talking about his experience at the Art Students League, Rosenquist said \"I studied only with the abstract artists. They had commercial artists there teaching commercial work, I didn't bother with that. I was only interested in -- see, here's how it started. I was interested in learning how to paint the Sistine Chapel. It sounds ambitious, but I wanted to go to mural school\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|title=James Rosenquist Studio|last=exhibit-e.com|website=www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> While studying in New York, Rosenquist took up a job as a chauffeur, before deciding to join the [[International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades of the United States and Canada|International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades]].  As a member of the union, Rosenquist would paint billboards around [[Times Square]], ultimately becoming the lead painter for [[Artkraft Strauss|Artkraft\u2010Strauss]] and painting displays and windows across Fifth Avenue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theartstory.org/artist-rosenquist-james.htm|title=James Rosenquist Biography, Art, and Analysis of Works|work=The Art Story|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref> By 1960, Rosenquist abandoned painting signs after a friend died by falling from scaffolding on the job.<ref name=\":2\" /> Instead of working on commercial pieces, he chose to focus on personal projects in his own studio, developing his own distinct style of painting that retained the kind of imagery, bold hues, and scale that he utilized while he painted billboards.\n\n==Career==\n\nRosenquist's career in commercial art began when he was 18, after his mother encouraged him to pursue a summer job painting. He started by painting [[Phillips 66]] signs, going to gas stations from North Dakota to Wisconsin. After leaving school, Rosenquist took a series of odd jobs and then turned to sign painting.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> From 1957 to 1960, Rosenquist earned his living as a [[billboard (advertising)|billboard]] painter. Rosenquist applied sign-painting techniques to the large-scale paintings he began creating in 1960. Like other pop artists, Rosenquist adapted the visual language of advertising and [[popular culture|pop culture]] to the context of fine art.<ref>{{cite web|title= James Rosenquist, The Bird of Paradise Approaches the Hot Water Planet, 1988, Oil on canvas, 105 x 85 inches|website= www.acquavellagalleries.com |publisher=Acquavella Galleries|url=  https://www.acquavellagalleries.com/artists/james-rosenquist}}</ref>\n\"I painted billboards above every candy store in Brooklyn. \"I got so I could paint a [[Schenley Industries|Schenley]] whiskey bottle in my sleep\", he wrote in his 2009 autobiography, ''Painting Below Zero: Notes on a Life in Art''.<ref name=\"theguardian\"/> ''Time'' magazine stated that \"his powerful graphic style and painted montages helped define the 1960s Pop Art movement.\"<ref>\"Milestones James Rosenquist,\" ''Time,'' April 17, 2017, p.&nbsp;15</ref>\n\nIn 2003, art critic [[Peter Schjeldahl]] asked of Rosenquist's application of [[sign painting]] techniques to fine art thus: \"[W]as importing the method into art a bit of a cheap trick? So were Warhol's photo silk-screening and Lichtenstein's lining of panels from comic strips. The goal in all cases was to fuse painting aesthetics with the semiotics of media-drenched contemporary reality. The naked efficiency of anti-personal artmaking defines classic Pop. It's as if someone were inviting you to inspect the fist with which he simultaneously punches you.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\nRosenquist had his first two solo exhibitions at the [[Green Gallery]] in 1962 and 1963.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> He exhibited his painting ''F-111'', a room-scale painting, at the [[Leo Castelli Gallery]] in 1965,<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> with which he achieved international acclaim.<ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17bpAAAAMAAJ |title=The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums |publisher=Museo Guggenheim Bilbao |year=2007 |page=162}}</ref>\n\nBut Rosenquist said the following about his involvement in the Pop Art movement: \"They [art critics] called me a Pop artist because I used recognizable imagery. The critics like to group people together. I didn't meet [[Andy Warhol]] until 1964. I did not really know Andy or [[Roy Lichtenstein]] that well. We all emerged separately.\"<ref>[http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2008/04/art-space-talk-james-rosenquist.html \"Art Space Talk: James Rosenquist\"], ''Myartspace'', April 4, 2008. Retrieved May 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1971 Rosenquist came to South Florida after receiving an offer from [[Donald Saff]], dean of the [[University of South Florida|University of South Florida's]] College of Fine Arts, to participate in the school's [[Graphicstudio]], a collaborative art initiative.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/obituaries/pop-art-giant-james-rosenquists-work-influenced-generations-from-new-york/2318804|title=James Rosenquist, who elevated the Tampa Bay art world, dead at 83|date=2017-04-02|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>  In the years following Rosenquist remained a key contributor to the studio, cooperating with students and other artists and producing numerous works of his own, ultimately creating his Aripeka studio in 1976.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rosenquist would continue to travel to Florida throughout his career with the artist developing several commissioned works for the community including two murals for Florida's state capitol building and a sculpture for [[Johns Hopkins All Children's Hospital]], in addition to serving on the [[Tampa Museum of Art|Tampa Museum of Art's]] Board of Trustees.<ref name=\"dos.myflorida.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/james-rosenquist/|title=James Rosenquist - Division of Cultural Affairs - Florida Department of State|website=dos.myflorida.com|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"dos.myflorida.com\"/>\n\nRosenquist's paintings have been on display in the lobby of [[Key Tower]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. His ''F-111'' was displayed there for many years.<ref>Litt, Steven. \"Salle Mural Quietly Fills Key Tower Void\", ''[[The Plain Dealer]]''. March 22, 1998.</ref>\n\nAfter his acclaim, Rosenquist produced large-scale commissions. This includes the three-painting suite ''The Swimmer'' ''in the Econo-mist'' (1997\u20131998) for [[Deutsche Guggenheim]], Berlin, Germany, and a painting that was planned for the ceiling of the [[Palais de Chaillot]] in Paris, France.<ref name=\"nationalpost\" />\n\n== Works ==\n''Zone'': A key work in the development of his signature style, Rosenquist cites his 1961 work ''Zone'' as a turning point in the development of his own personal aesthetic, with the piece being the first to employ monumental scale, a recurring aspect of Rosenquist's art that is exemplified in his many murals.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>(March 15, 2019). [https://www.artdesigncafe.com/james-rosenquist-zone-1961 James Rosenquist. ''Zone'', (1961)]. ''artdesigncafe''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref> ''Zone'' also served as a stepping stone in Rosenquist's body of work in that it served as a departure from his previous works, which saw him move away from previous experiments in [[Abstract expressionism|Abstract Expressionism]], with the picture being described by Rosenquist as his first pop piece.<ref name=\":1\" /> Done in oil on two separate  pieces of canvas, the work exemplifies the beginnings of the pop art movement in the way that Rosenquist takes imagery from mass media, using a picture of a tomato and a clipping from an ad for hand cream.<ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\" /> The two images are divided into separate zones, which serve to focus on visual parallels such as the arch of the tomato stem and the woman's eyelashes, as well as illustrating Rosenquist's signature, often surreal, fragmented composition.\n\n''President Elect'': Released the same year as ''Zone'', James Rosenquist's ''President Elect'' is among one his most well-known pieces, with the artist translating a portrait of [[John F. Kennedy]] from a campaign poster onto a towering display.<ref>Taylor, Alex J. (2017). [https://www.tate.org.uk/research/publications/in-focus/silo/the-painting \"The painting\"] [with photo of ''President elect'']. In Alex J. Taylor's (Ed.), ''In Focus: Silo 1963\u20134 by James Rosenquist''. Tate Research Publication: London. Retrieved April 5, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\" /> The painting also includes a superimposed picture of hand holding cake in greyscale, as well as the back of a Chevrolet. Rosenquist uses icons in pop culture to examine fame and the relationship between advertising and the consumer, exploring the kind of fame and iconography that comes with American politics. With ''President Elect'', Rosenquist seeks to make a statement on the new role that advertising and mass media had during the Kennedy's campaign. \"I was very interested at that time in people who advertised themselves,\" said Rosenquist. \"Why did they put up an advertisement of themselves? So that was his face. And his promise was half a Chevrolet and a piece of stale cake.\" In the painting, Rosenquist contrasts the portrait of Kennedy with the cake and the Chevrolet to show how each element is marketed to American consumers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''F-111'': In 1965, James Rosenquist completed ''F-111'', one of the largest and most ambitious works in his collection.<ref>(n.d.). [https://www.moma.org/collection/works/79805 James Rosenquist. ''F-111'', (1964-65)]. Museum of Modern Art, New York. Retrieved April 5, 2020.</ref> Spanning over 83 feet and 23 canvases, the painting's scale evokes Rosenquist's work on billboards, illustrating a life-sized depiction of the [[F-111 Aardvark]] aircraft.<ref name=\":1\" /> The painting initially was intended to cover all four walls of the main room within the [[Castelli Gallery|Castelli gallery]] in Manhattan, occupying the entirety of each wall without any kind of visual relief, to cast an imposing, continuous view of the war. Painted during the [[Vietnam War|Vietnam war]], ''F-111'' contrasts pictures from the war with commercial imagery from advertisements, showing tires, a cake, lightbulbs, a girl in a salon hairdryer, bubbles, and spaghetti. Rosenquist juxtaposes the imagery from the ads against the plane as a way to imply graphic scenes from the war, with broken light bulbs near the cockpit mirroring bombs dropping from the plane, and the hood of the hairdryer echoing the look of a missile. Rosenquist uses the painting to question the role of marketing and coverage of the war describing the plane as \"flying through the flak of consumer society to question the collusion between the Vietnam death machine, consumerism, the media, and advertising,\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Swenson|first=Gene|date=|title=An Interview with James Rosenquist|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/pubs/bulletins/1/pdf/3258336.pdf.bannered.pdf|journal=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin|volume=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n{{quote box\n| quote = To be creative is to be accepting, but it's also to be harsh on one's self. You just don't paint colors for the silliness of it all.\n|source= \u2013 James Rosenquist<ref>Staniszewski, Mary Anne. [http://bombsite.com/issues/21/articles/956 \"James Rosenquist Interview\"] ''[[BOMB Magazine]]'' Fall, 1987. Retrieved May 17, 2013.</ref>\n| width = 30%\n}}\n\nRosenquist received numerous honors, including selection as \"Art In America Young Talent USA\" in 1963, appointment to a six-year term on the Board of the [[National Council of the Arts]] in 1978,<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> and receiving the [[Golden Plate Award]] from the [[American Academy of Achievement]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title= Golden Plate Awardees of the American Academy of Achievement |website=www.achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url=  https://achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/#the-arts}}</ref> In 2002, the [[Fundaci\u00f3n Crist\u00f3bal Gabarr\u00f3n]] conferred upon him its annual international award for art, in recognition of his contributions to universal culture.<ref name=\"ropac\">{{Cite web |url=http://ropac.net/artist/james-rosenquist |title=James Rosenquist |website=ropac.net}}</ref>\n\nBeginning with his first early-career retrospectives in 1972 organized by the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York City, and the [[Wallraf-Richartz Museum]], [[Cologne]], Rosenquist's work was the subject of several gallery and museum exhibitions, both in the United States and abroad. The [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] organized a full-career retrospective in 2003, which traveled internationally, and was organized by curators [[Walter Hopps]] and Sarah Bancroft.<ref>Stevens, Mark, ''New York Magazine'' (October 20, 2003). [http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/art/reviews/n_9376/ King of Pop]</ref>\n\nHis ''F-111'', shown at [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]] in 1965,<ref>(April 3, 2017). [https://medium.com/the-jewish-museum/remembering-pop-artist-james-rosenquist-97995de192b3 Remembering Pop artist James Rosenquist]. Jewish Museum (New York) website. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref> was mentioned in a chapter of ''Polaroids from the Dead'' by [[Douglas Coupland]].<ref name=\"nationalpost\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/books/book-reviews/how-douglas-couplands-polaroids-from-the-dead-continues-to-be-a-touchstone-20-years-later |title=How Douglas Coupland's Polaroids from the Dead continues to be a touchstone 20 years later |last=Wiersema |first=Robert J. |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=National Post |date=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRosenquist married twice and had two children.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> With his first wife, Mary Lou Adams, whom he married on June 5, 1960,<ref name=\"Current Biography\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gIU3AAAAMAAJ |title=Current Biography |publisher=H. W. Wilson Company |year=1970 |volume=31 |page=40}}</ref> he had one child: John.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> His first marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> In 1976, a year after his divorce, he moved to [[Aripeka, Florida]]. His second wife was Mimi Thompson, whom he married on April 18, 1987, by whom he had one child: Lily.<ref name=\"The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives: M-Z\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzQOAQAAMAAJ |title=The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives: M\u2013Z |publisher=C. Scribner's Sons |year=2003 |isbn=9780684312224 |editor-last=O'Neill |editor-first=William L. |edition=illustrated |page=280}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\nOn April 25, 2009, a fire swept through [[Hernando County, Florida]], where Rosenquist had lived for 30 years, burning his house, studios, and warehouse. All of his paintings stored on his property were destroyed, including art for an upcoming show.<ref>[http://www.miamiherald.com/living/story/1023391.html Miamiherald.com]</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/28/arts/design/28arts-POPARTISTSWO_BRF.html?_r=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Pop Artist's Works Lost in Studio Fire | first=Dave | last=Itzkoff | date=April 28, 2009 | accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.baynews9.com/article/news/2009/april/51991/Famous-artists-home-paintings-destroyed-in-brushfire Baynews9.com]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nRosenquist died at his home in [[New York City]] on March 31, 2017, after a long illness; he was 83 years old.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/01/arts/james-rosenquist-dead-pop-art.html |title=James Rosenquist, Pop Art Pioneer, Dies at 83 |last=Johnson |first=Ken |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/apr/01/james-rosenquist-pop-artist-f-111-dies-83 |title=James Rosenquist, pop artist who painted the famous F-111, dies aged 83 |last=Pengelly  |first=Martin  |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 April 2017}}</ref> His survivors include his wife, Thompson; one daughter, Lily; one son, John; and a grandson, Oscar.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.jimrosenquist-artist.com/ Rosenquist's official site]\n* {{MoMA artist|5021}}\n* [http://nga.gov.au/InternationalPrints/Tyler/Default.cfm?MnuID=3&ArtistIRN=17537&List=True&CREIRN=17537&ORDER_SELECT=13&VIEW_SELECT=5&GrpNam=13&TNOTES=TRUE James Rosenquist in the National Gallery of Australia's Kenneth Tyler Collection]\n* [http://russblaise.com/rosenquist.html Photographs of James Rosenquist by photographer Russ Blaise]\n* [http://www.deutsche-bank-kunst.com/art/2003/14/e/4/147.php Interview with db artmag]\n* [https://achievement.org/achiever/james-rosenquist/#interview James Rosenquist Biography and Interview on American Academy of Achievement]\n* [http://www.popartmasters.com/toc.html#masters Pop Art Masters \u2013 James Rosenquist]\n* [http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist In the Studio: James Rosenquist]\n* [http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2008/04/art-space-talk-james-rosenquist.html Interview with Myartspace]\n* [http://www.jablonkagalerie.com Exhibition ''The Hole in the Center of Time'' with the latest works at Jablonka Galerie, Berlin]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716052553/https://residentassociates.org/ArtCollectors/gallery.aspx?index=615&artwork=216142 Rosenquist's ''Discover Graphics'', the Smithsonian Art Collectors Program.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080229065116/http://www.guggenheim.org/exhibitions/rosenquist/index.html ''James Rosenquist: A Retrospective'' at the Guggenheim Museum, New York City, 2003\u201304]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/28/books/28zero.html?hpw \"Rosenquist Writ Large, by Himself\", Dwight Garner, ''The New York Times'', October 27, 2009]\n* [http://bombsite.com/issues/21/articles/956 ''BOMB Magazine'' interview with James Rosenquist by Mary Anne Staniszewski (Fall, 1987)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924084909/http://www.rareposters.com/index.php/catalogsearch/result/index/?p=1&q=rosenquist Rosenquist Rare Exhibition Posters on Rare Posters]\n*[http://thejewishmuseum.org/collection/5513-the-flame-still-dances-on-leo-s-book James Rosenquist at the Jewish Museum.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenquist, James}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American pop artists]]\n[[Category:American painters]]\n[[Category:American printmakers]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:Art Students League of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Grand Forks, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Artists from North Dakota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = James Rosenquist\n| image         = James_rosenquist1.jpg\n| caption       = Photo by: Russ Blaise 1988\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1933|11|29|}}\n| birth_place    = [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age |2017|03|31 |1933|11|29}}\n| death_place    = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| field         = Painting, [[printmaking]], drawing\n| training      = [[Minneapolis College of Art and Design]]<br>[[University of Minnesota]]<br>[[Art Students League of New York]]\n| movement      = [[Pop art]]\n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| spouse = {{marriage|Mary Lou Adams|1960|1975|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|Mimi Thompson|1987}}\n| awards        = \n}}\n\n'''James Rosenquist''' (November 29, 1933 \u2013 March 31, 2017) was an American artist and one of the proponents of the [[pop art]] movement. Drawing from his background working in sign painting, Rosenquist's pieces often explored the role of advertising and consumer culture in art and society, utilizing techniques he learned making commercial art to depict popular cultural icons and mundane everyday objects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com/artist/biography|title=Biography - Artist - James Rosenquist Studio|last=exhibit-e.com|website=www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref> While his works have often been compared to those from other key figures of the pop art movement, such as [[Andy Warhol]] and [[Roy Lichtenstein]], Rosenquist's pieces were unique in the way that they often employed elements of surrealism using fragments of advertisements and cultural imagery to emphasize the overwhelming nature of ads.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theartstory.org/artist-rosenquist-james.htm|title=James Rosenquist Biography, Art, and Analysis of Works|work=The Art Story|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref> He was a 2001 inductee into the [[Florida Artists Hall of Fame]].<ref>[http://www.florida-arts.org/programs/ahf/displayArtist.cfm?member=31 James Rosenquist] Florida Artists Hall of Fame</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nRosenquist was born on November 29, 1933, in [[Grand Forks, North Dakota]],<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> the only child of Louis and Ruth Rosenquist. His parents were amateur pilots of [[Swedes|Swedish]] descent who moved from town to town to look for work, finally settling in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. His mother, who was also a painter, encouraged her son to have an artistic interest. In junior high school, Rosenquist won a short-term scholarship to study at the [[Minneapolis College of Art and Design|Minneapolis School of Art]] and subsequently studied painting at the [[University of Minnesota]] from 1952 to 1954.  In 1955, at the age of 21, he moved to [[New York, New York|New York City]] on scholarship to study at the [[Art Students League of New York|Art Students League]], studying under painters such as [[Edwin Dickinson]] and [[George Grosz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist/|title=In the Studio: James Rosenquist|last=Kastner|first=Jeffrey|date=November 22, 2007|publisher=artinfo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080524084109/http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist/|archivedate=May 24, 2008|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 21, 2008}}</ref> Talking about his experience at the Art Students League, Rosenquist said \"I studied only with the abstract artists. They had commercial artists there teaching commercial work, I didn't bother with that. I was only interested in -- see, here's how it started. I was interested in learning how to paint the Sistine Chapel. It sounds ambitious, but I wanted to go to mural school\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|title=James Rosenquist Studio|last=exhibit-e.com|website=www.jamesrosenquiststudio.com|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> While studying in New York, Rosenquist took up a job as a chauffeur, before deciding to join the [[International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades of the United States and Canada|International Brotherhood of Painters and Allied Trades]].  As a member of the union, Rosenquist would paint billboards around [[Times Square]], ultimately becoming the lead painter for [[Artkraft Strauss|Artkraft\u2010Strauss]] and painting displays and windows across Fifth Avenue.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theartstory.org/artist-rosenquist-james.htm|title=James Rosenquist Biography, Art, and Analysis of Works|work=The Art Story|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US}}</ref> By 1960, Rosenquist abandoned painting signs after a friend died by falling from scaffolding on the job.<ref name=\":2\" /> Instead of working on commercial pieces, he chose to focus on personal projects in his own studio, developing his own distinct style of painting that retained the kind of imagery, bold hues, and scale that he utilized while he painted billboards.\n\n==Career==\n\nRosenquist's career in commercial art began when he was 18, after his mother encouraged him to pursue a summer job painting. He started by painting [[Phillips 66]] signs, going to gas stations from North Dakota to Wisconsin. After leaving school, Rosenquist took a series of odd jobs and then turned to sign painting.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> From 1957 to 1960, Rosenquist earned his living as a [[billboard (advertising)|billboard]] painter. Rosenquist applied sign-painting techniques to the large-scale paintings he began creating in 1960. Like other pop artists, Rosenquist adapted the visual language of advertising and [[popular culture|pop culture]] to the context of fine art.<ref>{{cite web|title= James Rosenquist, The Bird of Paradise Approaches the Hot Water Planet, 1988, Oil on canvas, 105 x 85 inches|website= www.acquavellagalleries.com |publisher=Acquavella Galleries|url=  https://www.acquavellagalleries.com/artists/james-rosenquist}}</ref>\n\"I painted billboards above every candy store in Brooklyn. \"I got so I could paint a [[Schenley Industries|Schenley]] whiskey bottle in my sleep\", he wrote in his 2009 autobiography, ''Painting Below Zero: Notes on a Life in Art''.<ref name=\"theguardian\"/> ''Time'' magazine stated that \"his powerful graphic style and painted montages helped define the 1960s Pop Art movement.\"<ref>\"Milestones James Rosenquist,\" ''Time,'' April 17, 2017, p.&nbsp;15</ref>\n\nIn 2003, art critic [[Peter Schjeldahl]] asked of Rosenquist's application of [[sign painting]] techniques to fine art thus: \"[W]as importing the method into art a bit of a cheap trick? So were Warhol's photo silk-screening and Lichtenstein's lining of panels from comic strips. The goal in all cases was to fuse painting aesthetics with the semiotics of media-drenched contemporary reality. The naked efficiency of anti-personal artmaking defines classic Pop. It's as if someone were inviting you to inspect the fist with which he simultaneously punches you.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\nRosenquist had his first two solo exhibitions at the [[Green Gallery]] in 1962 and 1963.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> He exhibited his painting ''F-111'', a room-scale painting, at the [[Leo Castelli Gallery]] in 1965,<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> with which he achieved international acclaim.<ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=17bpAAAAMAAJ |title=The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums |publisher=Museo Guggenheim Bilbao |year=2007 |page=162}}</ref>\n\nBut Rosenquist said the following about his involvement in the Pop Art movement: \"They [art critics] called me a Pop artist because I used recognizable imagery. The critics like to group people together. I didn't meet [[Andy Warhol]] until 1964. I did not really know Andy or [[Roy Lichtenstein]] that well. We all emerged separately.\"<ref>[http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2008/04/art-space-talk-james-rosenquist.html \"Art Space Talk: James Rosenquist\"], ''Myartspace'', April 4, 2008. Retrieved May 16, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 1971 Rosenquist came to South Florida after receiving an offer from [[Donald Saff]], dean of the [[University of South Florida|University of South Florida's]] College of Fine Arts, to participate in the school's [[Graphicstudio]], a collaborative art initiative.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/obituaries/pop-art-giant-james-rosenquists-work-influenced-generations-from-new-york/2318804|title=James Rosenquist, who elevated the Tampa Bay art world, dead at 83|date=2017-04-02|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>  In the years following Rosenquist remained a key contributor to the studio, cooperating with students and other artists and producing numerous works of his own, ultimately creating his Aripeka studio in 1976.<ref name=\":0\" /> Rosenquist would continue to travel to Florida throughout his career with the artist developing several commissioned works for the community including two murals for Florida's state capitol building and a sculpture for [[Johns Hopkins All Children's Hospital]], in addition to serving on the [[Tampa Museum of Art|Tampa Museum of Art's]] Board of Trustees.<ref name=\"dos.myflorida.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://dos.myflorida.com/cultural/programs/florida-artists-hall-of-fame/james-rosenquist/|title=James Rosenquist - Division of Cultural Affairs - Florida Department of State|website=dos.myflorida.com|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\"dos.myflorida.com\"/>\n\nRosenquist's paintings have been on display in the lobby of [[Key Tower]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. His ''F-111'' was displayed there for many years.<ref>Litt, Steven. \"Salle Mural Quietly Fills Key Tower Void\", ''[[The Plain Dealer]]''. March 22, 1998.</ref>\n\nAfter his acclaim, Rosenquist produced large-scale commissions. This includes the three-painting suite ''The Swimmer'' ''in the Econo-mist'' (1997\u20131998) for [[Deutsche Guggenheim]], Berlin, Germany, and a painting that was planned for the ceiling of the [[Palais de Chaillot]] in Paris, France.<ref name=\"nationalpost\" />\n\n== Works ==\n''Zone'': A key work in the development of his signature style, Rosenquist cites his 1961 work ''Zone'' as a turning point in the development of his own personal aesthetic, with the piece being the first to employ monumental scale, a recurring aspect of Rosenquist's art that is exemplified in his many murals.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>(March 15, 2019). [https://www.artdesigncafe.com/james-rosenquist-zone-1961 James Rosenquist. ''Zone'', (1961)]. ''artdesigncafe''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref> ''Zone'' also served as a stepping stone in Rosenquist's body of work in that it served as a departure from his previous works, which saw him move away from previous experiments in [[Abstract expressionism|Abstract Expressionism]], with the picture being described by Rosenquist as his first pop piece.<ref name=\":1\" /> Done in oil on two separate  pieces of canvas, the work exemplifies the beginnings of the pop art movement in the way that Rosenquist takes imagery from mass media, using a picture of a tomato and a clipping from an ad for hand cream.<ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\" /> The two images are divided into separate zones, which serve to focus on visual parallels such as the arch of the tomato stem and the woman's eyelashes, as well as illustrating Rosenquist's signature, often surreal, fragmented composition.\n\n''President Elect'': Released the same year as ''Zone'', James Rosenquist's ''President Elect'' is among one his most well-known pieces, with the artist translating a portrait of [[John F. Kennedy]] from a campaign poster onto a towering display.<ref>Taylor, Alex J. (2017). [https://www.tate.org.uk/research/publications/in-focus/silo/the-painting \"The painting\"] [with photo of ''President elect'']. In Alex J. Taylor's (Ed.), ''In Focus: Silo 1963\u20134 by James Rosenquist''. Tate Research Publication: London. Retrieved April 5, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"The Permanent Collections of the Guggenheim Museums\" /> The painting also includes a superimposed picture of hand holding cake in greyscale, as well as the back of a Chevrolet. Rosenquist uses icons in pop culture to examine fame and the relationship between advertising and the consumer, exploring the kind of fame and iconography that comes with American politics. With ''President Elect'', Rosenquist seeks to make a statement on the new role that advertising and mass media had during the Kennedy's campaign. \"I was very interested at that time in people who advertised themselves,\" said Rosenquist. \"Why did they put up an advertisement of themselves? So that was his face. And his promise was half a Chevrolet and a piece of stale cake.\" In the painting, Rosenquist contrasts the portrait of Kennedy with the cake and the Chevrolet to show how each element is marketed to American consumers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n''F-111'': In 1965, James Rosenquist completed ''F-111'', one of the largest and most ambitious works in his collection.<ref>(n.d.). [https://www.moma.org/collection/works/79805 James Rosenquist. ''F-111'', (1964-65)]. Museum of Modern Art, New York. Retrieved April 5, 2020.</ref> Spanning over 83 feet and 23 canvases, the painting's scale evokes Rosenquist's work on billboards, illustrating a life-sized depiction of the [[F-111 Aardvark]] aircraft.<ref name=\":1\" /> The painting initially was intended to cover all four walls of the main room within the [[Castelli Gallery|Castelli gallery]] in Manhattan, occupying the entirety of each wall without any kind of visual relief, to cast an imposing, continuous view of the war. Painted during the [[Vietnam War|Vietnam war]], ''F-111'' contrasts pictures from the war with commercial imagery from advertisements, showing tires, a cake, lightbulbs, a girl in a salon hairdryer, bubbles, and spaghetti. Rosenquist juxtaposes the imagery from the ads against the plane as a way to imply graphic scenes from the war, with broken light bulbs near the cockpit mirroring bombs dropping from the plane, and the hood of the hairdryer echoing the look of a missile. Rosenquist uses the painting to question the role of marketing and coverage of the war describing the plane as \"flying through the flak of consumer society to question the collusion between the Vietnam death machine, consumerism, the media, and advertising,\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Swenson|first=Gene|date=|title=An Interview with James Rosenquist|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/pubs/bulletins/1/pdf/3258336.pdf.bannered.pdf|journal=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin|volume=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\n{{quote box\n| quote = To be creative is to be accepting, but it's also to be harsh on one's self. You just don't paint colors for the silliness of it all.\n|source= \u2013 James Rosenquist<ref>Staniszewski, Mary Anne. [http://bombsite.com/issues/21/articles/956 \"James Rosenquist Interview\"] ''[[BOMB Magazine]]'' Fall, 1987. Retrieved May 17, 2013.</ref>\n| width = 30%\n}}\n\nRosenquist received numerous honors, including selection as \"Art In America Young Talent USA\" in 1963, appointment to a six-year term on the Board of the [[National Council of the Arts]] in 1978,<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> and receiving the [[Golden Plate Award]] from the [[American Academy of Achievement]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title= Golden Plate Awardees of the American Academy of Achievement |website=www.achievement.org|publisher=[[American Academy of Achievement]]|url=  https://achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/#the-arts}}</ref> In 2002, the [[Fundaci\u00f3n Crist\u00f3bal Gabarr\u00f3n]] conferred upon him its annual international award for art, in recognition of his contributions to universal culture.<ref name=\"ropac\">{{Cite web |url=http://ropac.net/artist/james-rosenquist |title=James Rosenquist |website=ropac.net}}</ref>\n\nBeginning with his first early-career retrospectives in 1972 organized by the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York City, and the [[Wallraf-Richartz Museum]], [[Cologne]], Rosenquist's work was the subject of several gallery and museum exhibitions, both in the United States and abroad. The [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] organized a full-career retrospective in 2003, which traveled internationally, and was organized by curators [[Walter Hopps]] and Sarah Bancroft.<ref>Stevens, Mark, ''New York Magazine'' (October 20, 2003). [http://nymag.com/nymetro/arts/art/reviews/n_9376/ King of Pop]</ref>\n\nHis ''F-111'', shown at [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]] in 1965,<ref>(April 3, 2017). [https://medium.com/the-jewish-museum/remembering-pop-artist-james-rosenquist-97995de192b3 Remembering Pop artist James Rosenquist]. Jewish Museum (New York) website. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref> was mentioned in a chapter of ''Polaroids from the Dead'' by [[Douglas Coupland]].<ref name=\"nationalpost\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/books/book-reviews/how-douglas-couplands-polaroids-from-the-dead-continues-to-be-a-touchstone-20-years-later |title=How Douglas Coupland's Polaroids from the Dead continues to be a touchstone 20 years later |last=Wiersema |first=Robert J. |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=National Post |date=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRosenquist married twice and had two children.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> With his first wife, Mary Lou Adams, whom he married on June 5, 1960,<ref name=\"Current Biography\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gIU3AAAAMAAJ |title=Current Biography |publisher=H. W. Wilson Company |year=1970 |volume=31 |page=40}}</ref> he had one child: John.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> His first marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /> In 1976, a year after his divorce, he moved to [[Aripeka, Florida]]. His second wife was Mimi Thompson, whom he married on April 18, 1987, by whom he had one child:<ref name=\"The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives: M-Z\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzQOAQAAMAAJ |title=The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives: M\u2013Z |publisher=C. Scribner's Sons |year=2003 |isbn=9780684312224 |editor-last=O'Neill |editor-first=William L. |edition=illustrated |page=280}}</ref> Lily.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\nOn April 25, 2009, a fire swept through [[Hernando County, Florida]], where Rosenquist had lived for 30 years, burning his house, studios, and warehouse. All of his paintings stored on his property were destroyed, including art for an upcoming show.<ref>[http://www.miamiherald.com/living/story/1023391.html Miamiherald.com]</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/28/arts/design/28arts-POPARTISTSWO_BRF.html?_r=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Pop Artist's Works Lost in Studio Fire | first=Dave | last=Itzkoff | date=April 28, 2009 | accessdate=October 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.baynews9.com/article/news/2009/april/51991/Famous-artists-home-paintings-destroyed-in-brushfire Baynews9.com]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nRosenquist died at his home in [[New York City]] on March 31, 2017, after a long illness; he was 83 years old.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/01/arts/james-rosenquist-dead-pop-art.html |title=James Rosenquist, Pop Art Pioneer, Dies at 83 |last=Johnson |first=Ken |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=1 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"theguardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2017/apr/01/james-rosenquist-pop-artist-f-111-dies-83 |title=James Rosenquist, pop artist who painted the famous F-111, dies aged 83 |last=Pengelly  |first=Martin  |access-date=2 April 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 April 2017}}</ref> His survivors include his wife, Thompson; one daughter, Lily; one son, John; and a grandson, Oscar.<ref name=\"nytimes\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.jimrosenquist-artist.com/ Rosenquist's official site]\n* {{MoMA artist|5021}}\n* [http://nga.gov.au/InternationalPrints/Tyler/Default.cfm?MnuID=3&ArtistIRN=17537&List=True&CREIRN=17537&ORDER_SELECT=13&VIEW_SELECT=5&GrpNam=13&TNOTES=TRUE James Rosenquist in the National Gallery of Australia's Kenneth Tyler Collection]\n* [http://russblaise.com/rosenquist.html Photographs of James Rosenquist by photographer Russ Blaise]\n* [http://www.deutsche-bank-kunst.com/art/2003/14/e/4/147.php Interview with db artmag]\n* [https://achievement.org/achiever/james-rosenquist/#interview James Rosenquist Biography and Interview on American Academy of Achievement]\n* [http://www.popartmasters.com/toc.html#masters Pop Art Masters \u2013 James Rosenquist]\n* [http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/25939/in-the-studio-james-rosenquist In the Studio: James Rosenquist]\n* [http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2008/04/art-space-talk-james-rosenquist.html Interview with Myartspace]\n* [http://www.jablonkagalerie.com Exhibition ''The Hole in the Center of Time'' with the latest works at Jablonka Galerie, Berlin]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716052553/https://residentassociates.org/ArtCollectors/gallery.aspx?index=615&artwork=216142 Rosenquist's ''Discover Graphics'', the Smithsonian Art Collectors Program.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080229065116/http://www.guggenheim.org/exhibitions/rosenquist/index.html ''James Rosenquist: A Retrospective'' at the Guggenheim Museum, New York City, 2003\u201304]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/28/books/28zero.html?hpw \"Rosenquist Writ Large, by Himself\", Dwight Garner, ''The New York Times'', October 27, 2009]\n* [http://bombsite.com/issues/21/articles/956 ''BOMB Magazine'' interview with James Rosenquist by Mary Anne Staniszewski (Fall, 1987)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924084909/http://www.rareposters.com/index.php/catalogsearch/result/index/?p=1&q=rosenquist Rosenquist Rare Exhibition Posters on Rare Posters]\n*[http://thejewishmuseum.org/collection/5513-the-flame-still-dances-on-leo-s-book James Rosenquist at the Jewish Museum.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenquist, James}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American pop artists]]\n[[Category:American painters]]\n[[Category:American printmakers]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:Art Students League of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Grand Forks, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:Artists from North Dakota]]\n", "name_user": "Mrdnartdesign", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:moved ref for cleaner presentation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Rosenquist"}
